rial-for-gastric-cancer/81251888 |archive-date=2015-10-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies established in 1981]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Pharmaceutical companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Health care companies based in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{biotech-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Johnivan1994", "label": "safe", "comment": "ImmunoGen has 75 employees", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ImmunoGen"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Japan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan\n| map1 = COVID-19 outbreak Japan per capita cases map.svg{{!}}upright=1.7\n| legend1 = Confirmed cases per million residents by prefecture{{ref|a}}\n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = {{Flag|Japan}}\n| first_case = [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]\n| arrival_date = 16 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=16|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China\n| recovery_cases = 2,536<ref name=\"mhlw\"/>\n| deaths = 345<ref name=\"mhlw\">{{cite web |title=\u56fd\u5185\u611f\u67d3\u78ba\u8a8d\uff11\u4e072863\u4eba 345\u4eba\u6b7b\u4ea1\uff08\u6a2a\u6d5c\u6e2f\u306e\u30af\u30eb\u30fc\u30ba\u8239\u9664\u304f\uff09 |url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/special/coronavirus/?cid=dchk-commonheader |website=NHK\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 12,863<ref name=\"mhlw\"/>\n| active_cases = 10,327<ref name=\"mhlw\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Japan]] in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/don/16-january-2020-novel-coronavirus-japan-ex-china/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Novel Coronavirus \u2013 Japan (ex-China)|website=WHO|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Cases have been recorded in each of the 47 [[Prefectures of Japan|prefectures]] except for [[Iwate Prefecture|Iwate]]. The country has seen over 10,000 confirmed cases.\n\nThe Japanese government has adopted various measures for the prevention and mitigation of the outbreak after the first known case of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}) in the country was confirmed on 16 January 2020 in a resident of [[Kanagawa Prefecture]] who had returned from [[Wuhan]], [[China]]. On 30 January, Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] established a [[:ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u672c\u90e8|national task force]] to oversee the government's response to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202001/_00034.html|title=Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters|last=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  On 27 February, he requested the temporary closure of all Japanese elementary, junior high, and high schools until early April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/c3c57bbce11d-breaking-news-govt-will-ask-all-schools-in-japan-to-shut-for-virus-fears-abe.html|title=PM Abe asks all schools in Japan to temporarily close over coronavirus|publisher=Kyodo News}}</ref> As the pandemic became a concern for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], the Japanese government and the [[International Olympic Committee]] negotiated its postponement until 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tokyo 2020 Olympics officially postponed until 2021 |url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28946033/tokyo-olympics-officially-postponed-2021 |publisher=ESPN |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 7 April, Abe proclaimed a one-month [[state of emergency]] for Tokyo and the prefectures of [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]], [[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]], [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], [[Osaka Prefecture|Osaka]], [[Hy\u014dgo Prefecture|Hyogo]], and [[Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-07/japan-s-abe-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Japan Declares Emergency For Tokyo, Osaka as Hospitals Fill Up|first1=Isabel|last1=Reynolds|first2=Emi|last2=Nobuhiro|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> On 16 April, the declaration was extended to the rest of the country.<ref name=\"416emergency\">{{cite news|title=Japan PM Abe declares nationwide state of emergency amid virus spread|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200416/p2g/00m/0na/085000c|publisher=Mainichi Shimbun|date=16 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Japan medical cases chart}}\n\n===January===\nA resident of Kanagawa Prefecture in his 30s who had previously travelled to [[Wuhan]] developed a fever on 3 January and subsequently returned to Japan on 6 January. He tested positive during a hospital admission between 10 and 15 January. He had not visited the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], but may have had close contact with an affected person in Wuhan.<ref name=\"Walter16Jan2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/japan-confirms-first-case-of-infection-with-new-china-coronavirus|title=Japan confirms first case of infection from Wuhan coronavirus; Vietnam quarantines two tourists|last=Walter|first=Sim|date=16 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116072051/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/japan-confirms-first-case-of-infection-with-new-china-coronavirus|archive-date=16 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO=16Jan2020\">{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/don/16-january-2020-novel-coronavirus-japan-ex-china/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Novel Coronavirus \u2013 Japan (ex-China)|website=WHO|url-status=live|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January, the second case was confirmed in a Chinese national who visited from Wuhan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/01/70da752ed169-urgent-japan-confirms-2nd-new-coronavirus-infection.html |title=Japan confirms 2nd new virus case, braces for Chinese tourist influx |date=24 January 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |access-date=8 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201162315/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/01/70da752ed169-urgent-japan-confirms-2nd-new-coronavirus-infection.html |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 January, the third case was confirmed in a woman from Wuhan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/25/national/japan-confirms-third-case-new-coronavirus/|title=Japan confirms third case of new coronavirus infection|date=25 January 2020|newspaper=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\nAfterwards, Japan took extra precautions, due to the upcoming [[2020 Summer Olympics]] being held in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus spotlights Japan contagion risks as Olympics loom|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-china-virus/coronavirus-spotlights-japan-contagion-risks-as-olympics-loom-idUSKBN1ZM0YJ|agency=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|first1=Rocky|last1=Swift|access-date=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124225619/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-china-virus/coronavirus-spotlights-japan-contagion-risks-as-olympics-loom-idUSKBN1ZM0YJ|archive-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, on 28 January, the fifth, sixth, and seventh cases were confirmed in Japan, including a man who had not visited Wuhan, but had been a tour bus driver for a group from Wuhan earlier in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/01/e8f47252a245-urgent-japan-sees-1st-coronavirus-case-not-linked-to-recent-travel-to-china.html|title=Japan sees 1st coronavirus case not linked to recent travel to China|date=28 January 2020|agency=Kyodo News|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129162636/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/01/e8f47252a245-urgent-japan-sees-1st-coronavirus-case-not-linked-to-recent-travel-to-china.html|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/28/national/japan-charter-flights-evacuate-japanese-virus-wuhan-china/#.XjAFCLdlB-E|title=Japan reports new coronavirus cases as it moves to evacuate nationals from Wuhan|date=28 January 2020|newspaper=Japan Times|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128134009/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/28/national/japan-charter-flights-evacuate-japanese-virus-wuhan-china/#.XjAFCLdlB-E|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The tour guide for that group also tested positive for [[SARS-CoV-2]].<ref name=\"test\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/evacuation-of-japanese-citizens-from-wuhan-in-spotlight-after-two-returnees-refuse|title=Wuhan virus: Evacuation of Japanese citizens from China in spotlight after two returnees refuse testing|date=30 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131174249/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/evacuation-of-japanese-citizens-from-wuhan-in-spotlight-after-two-returnees-refuse|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 January, a Chinese man and woman in their 40s tested positive in [[Aichi]] and in [[Hokkaido]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://japantoday.com/category/national/update2-japan-sees-1st-coronavirus-case-not-linked-to-recent-travel-to-china | title=Japan confirms 1st domestic case of coronavirus infection | access-date=8 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202073703/https://japantoday.com/category/national/update2-japan-sees-1st-coronavirus-case-not-linked-to-recent-travel-to-china |archive-date=2 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, three Japanese nationals who arrived at [[Haneda Airport]] after being evacuated from Wuhan tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020013000435/new-coronavirus-detected-in-3-japanese-returnees-from-wuhan.html|title=New Coronavirus Detected in 3 Japanese Returnees from Wuhan|date=30 January 2020|website=nippon.com|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130041422/https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020013000435/new-coronavirus-detected-in-3-japanese-returnees-from-wuhan.html|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Three other cases were confirmed later that day. Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] announced that two of those who came back via Haneda had refused further testing and said that officials could not legally force them to do so.<ref name=\"test\" /> It was announced on 31 January that the two had recanted their refusals and allowed further testing.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/01/1cfe46579ca4-breaking-news-japan-to-raise-china-travel-advisory-level-abe.html |title=Japan gov't criticized over initial coronavirus response | access-date=8 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203012817/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/01/1cfe46579ca4-breaking-news-japan-to-raise-china-travel-advisory-level-abe.html | archive-date=3 February 2020 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nOn 1 February, a 37-year-old man of the [[Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department]] working for the [[Cabinet Secretariat (Japan)|Cabinet Secretariat]], which was responsible for the evacuation of citizens from Wuhan and other related matters, died at [[National Institute of Public Health of Japan|National Institute of Public Health]] in [[Saitama Prefecture]]. The institute was where some of the evacuees from Wuhan stayed under temporary quarantine. Police are investigating the man's cause of death, but they suspect he was suicidal.<ref name=\"Japtimessuicide\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/02/national/crime-legal/japanese-official-looking-wuhan-returnees-found-dead/|title=Japanese official looking after Wuhan returnees found dead|date=2 February 2020|newspaper=The Japan Times Online|accessdate=15 March 2020|publisher=The Japan Times}}</ref>\n\nFrom 3 February, Japan forbade anyone who had had history of travelling to and from [[Hubei Province]] or had a Chinese passport officially issued from Hubei.<ref name=\"JENotice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ph.emb-japan.go.jp/itpr_en/00_001075.html|title=Important Notice on New Restrictions related to Novel Coronavirus : Embassy of Japan in the Philippines|website=ph.emb-japan.go.jp|date=3 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203045120/https://www.ph.emb-japan.go.jp/itpr_en/00_001075.html|archive-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, non-Japanese travellers were required to fill out health declaration questionnaires on whether they had (or would have) travelled to Hubei within the next 14 days.<ref name=\"JENotice\" />\n\nOn 11 February, two evacuees from Wuhan tested positive after an earlier test gave negative results.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nohara |first1=Yoshiaki |last2=Furukawa |first2=Yuki |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-11/two-japan-evacuees-get-coronavirus-after-first-testing-negative |title=Two Japan Evacuees Get Coronavirus After First Testing Negative |work=Bloomberg |date=11 February 2020 |access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Another three cases were confirmed over the next two days and brought the total national count to 31.<ref name=\"TJT13Feb\">{{cite news |title=Tokyo taxi driver and Wakayama surgeon test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/13/national/science-health/tokyo-taxi-driver-coronavirus/ |newspaper=The Japan Times Online |accessdate=13 February 2020 |date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February, Japan announced entry restrictions for anyone who had travelled to and from [[Zhejiang]] or had a Chinese passport issued from Zhejiang.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Japan-expands-entry-restrictions-to-virus-hit-Zhejiang|title=Japan expands entry restrictions to virus-hit Zhejiang|website=Nikkei Asian Review |access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February, a woman in her 80s died in [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], next to Tokyo, marking the first death from [[COVID-19]] in Japan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan confirms its first COVID-19 death: Health minister |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/japan-confirms-first-covid-19-coronavirus-death-12432316 |website=CNA |accessdate=13 February 2020 |date=13 February 2020}}</ref> She was the mother-in-law of a cab driver working in Tokyo who was also confirmed positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/13/national/science-health/tokyo-taxi-driver-coronavirus/|title=Japan reports first COVID-19 death as three more domestic infection cases logged|date=13 February 2020|work=Japan Times|access-date=15 February 2020 |issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, a married couple, both in their 60s, tested positive after returning from a ten-day vacation in Hawaii, during which the man began showing symptoms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200215/p2g/00m/0in/028000c|title=Japanese man who visited Hawaii confirmed with coronavirus|work=The Mainichi|date=15 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/14/us/coronavirus-hawaii-japan.html|title=Couple Tests Positive for Coronavirus After Returning From Vacation in Hawaii|work=The New York Times|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> On 16 February, it was reported that they had used [[Delta Air Lines]] to return to Tokyo from [[Oahu]] and stayed at the [[Grand Waikikian]].<ref name=\"KHONR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/couple-from-japan-later-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-took-delta-airlines-flight/|title=Couple from Japan later diagnosed with coronavirus took Delta Airlines flight|date=17 February 2020|publisher=khon2.com}}</ref> Contact tracing was initiated by the airline to confirm whether anyone was infected.<ref name=\"KHONR\" />\n\nOn 18 February, [[Wakayama Prefecture]] announced that three people tested positive.<ref name=\"WYMA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020021800842/3-more-in-japan%27s-wakayama-confirmed-infected-with-coronavirus.html|title=3 More in Japan's Wakayama Confirmed Infected with Coronavirus|date=18 February 2020|website=nippon.com}}</ref> The other two were a doctor who tested positive and a nurse in his 30s who worked as a member of the Disaster Medical Assistance Team after being deployed to the [[Diamond Princess (ship)|''Diamond Princess'']].<ref name=\"WYMA\" />\n\nOn 19 February, testing the 3,011 cases on the Diamond Princess was completed.<ref name=\"20200219 update\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/newpage_09640.html|title=\u6a2a\u6d5c\u6e2f\u3067\u691c\u75ab\u4e2d\u306e\u30af\u30eb\u30fc\u30ba\u8239\u5185\u3067\u78ba\u8a8d\u3055\u308c\u305f\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\uff08\u7b2c\uff11\uff13\u5831\uff09|website=www.mhlw.go.jp}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February, [[Fukuoka Prefecture]] announced its first virus case: a Japanese man in his sixties with no travel history overseas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fukuoka-now.com/en/news/first-covid-19-coronavirus-in-fukuoka/|title=First COVID-19 Coronavirus in Fukuoka|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, two elementary school boys in [[Hokkaido]] and one preschool school boy were confirmed to test positive for [[SARS-CoV-2]]; the latter had came back from an airlift out of Wuhan with his father, who was also tested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jen.jiji.com/jc/eng?g=eco&k=2020022101117|title=(Update) 2 Hokkaido Boys Infected with New Coronavirus \u2013 JIJI PRESS|website=jen.jiji.com}}</ref> The Diamond Princess' passengers disembarked.\n\nOn 22 February, a junior high school teacher working in [[Chiba Prefecture]] tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jen.jiji.com/jc/eng?g=eco&k=2020022200518|title=(Update 2) Teacher in Chiba Found Infected with Coronavirus \u2013 JIJI PRESS|website=jen.jiji.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February, the [[US State Department]] advised American visitors in Japan to be cautious due to the community spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/36799dcc49ca-urgent-us-raises-travel-alert-to-japan-due-to-community-spread-of-virus.html|title=U.S. raises travel alert to Japan due to \"community spread\" of virus|first=KYODO|last=NEWS|website=Kyodo News+}}</ref> On the same day the [[Nagoya Expressway|Nagoya Expressway Public Corporation]] announced plans to temporarily close some toll gates and let employees work from their homes after an employee staffing the toll gates was diagnosed positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"NEPC news\">{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200223/k10012297741000.html|title=\u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u9ad8\u901f \u6599\u91d1\u6240\u4e8b\u52d9\u54e1\u304c\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u611f\u67d3 \uff16\u6599\u91d1\u6240\u3092\u9589\u9396|website=NHK\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9}}</ref> Due to personnel shortages, six toll gates on the [[Route 4 (Nagoya Expressway)|T\u014dkai]] and [[Route 5 (Nagoya Expressway)|Manba]] routes of the expressway network were closed over the weekend.<ref name=\"NEPC news\" />\n[[File:Shibuya (49476143743).jpg|thumb|People in Tokyo wearing masks|alt=]]\nOn 25 February, the [[Shikoku]] region reported its first case in [[Tokushima Prefecture]], a former passenger of the Diamond Princess Cruise Ship who had originally tested negative a week earlier when disembarking from the ship.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13165283|title=Coronavirus outbreak hits Shikoku, Nagano for first time|date=26 February 2020|website=The Asahi Shimbun|accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, [[Shinzo Abe]] requested closing all elementary, junior high, and high schools to curb the spread of the infections from 2 March to the end of spring vacations, which usually conclude in early April.<ref>[https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/c3c57bbce11d-breaking-news-govt-will-ask-all-schools-in-japan-to-shut-for-virus-fears-abe.html \"PM Abe asks all schools in Japan to temporarily close over coronavirus\"]. ''Kyodo News'', 27 February 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=All schools in Japan told to close until April over virus outbreak|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/27/national/hokkaido-coronavirus-school/#.XlehiyNS-00|publisher=[[The Japan Times]]|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=27 February 2020|newspaper=The Japan Times Online}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 4 March, a 57-year-old man refused to wait at home after testing positive for COVID-19, and went to a bar and restaurant until he decided to go to the hospital. A female bar owner in her 30s tested positive on 12 March. The man died in the hospital on 18 March according to JHWLM's official confirmed cases report.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200318_49/|title=Man who tried to scatter coronavirus dies|website=[[NHK World-Japan]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Japan announced new [[quarantine]] restrictions to be enforced for all visitors coming from China and South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/covid19-japan-quarantine-visitors-china-south-korea-12505002|title=Japan to quarantine visitors from China, South Korea: Report|website=CNA|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n[[Shiga Prefecture]] announced its first case.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nOn 6 March, South Korea protested against the quarantine measures for South Koreans going to Japan by suspending visas for Japanese citizens travelling to South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southkorea-idUSKBN20T03O |title=South Korea suspends visas for Japanese in tit-for-tat coronavirus curbs |date=7 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020 |website=reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March, Hiroshima announced that one resident had been confirmed positive after visiting four hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20200309-00010000-chugoku-soci|date=9 March 2020|title=\u5e83\u5cf6\u5e02\u300c\u53d7\u8a3a\u5148\u306e\u6fc3\u539a\u63a5\u89e61\u4eba\u300d\u3000\u533b\u7642\u6a5f\u95a2\u540d\u516c\u8868\u6c42\u3081\u308b\u58f0|publisher=[[Yahoo! Japan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, four fatal cases caused by COVID-19 were found around Japan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020031300124/4-more-fatal-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-japan.html|date=13 March 2020|title=4 More Fatal Coronavirus Cases Confirmed in Japan|website=[[Jiji Press]]|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, NHK reported that the Japanese government planned to expand entry restrictions to foreigners arriving from four additional countries. The restrictions applied to three areas in Spain (including Madrid), four areas in Italy (including the northern region of [[Liguria]]), Switzerland's [[Ticino]] region, and all of Iceland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200317_12/ |title=Japan to expand entry ban to more European regions |date=16 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020 |website=njk.or.jp}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the governors of Osaka and Hyogo prefectures asked residents to avoid nonessential travel between the two neighbouring western Japan prefectures over the three-day weekend starting on 20 March to contain the spread of the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200319_49/|date=19 March 2020|title=People asked to refrain from Osaka-Hyogo travel|website=[[NHK World]]|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020031901351/residents-asked-to-refrain-from-osaka-hyogo-travel.html|date=19 March 2020|title=Residents Asked to Refrain from Osaka-Hyogo Travel|website=Nippon.com|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The three-week state of emergency in Hokkaido was lifted.<ref name=\"npr_hokkaido\">[https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/13/832981899/emergency-declared-in-japanese-prefecture-hit-by-2nd-wave-of-coronavirus-infecti Emergency Declared In Japanese Prefecture Hit By 2nd Wave Of Coronavirus Infections]</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Okayama confirmed its first case, a woman in her 60s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanyonews.jp/article/996148|date=22 March 2020|title=\u5ca1\u5c71\u3067\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u611f\u67d3\u521d\u78ba\u8a8d\u3000\u5e02\u9577\u3089\u300c\u611f\u67d3\u62e1\u5927\u9632\u6b62\u306b\u5168\u529b\u300d|publisher=[[Sanyo Shimbun]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Okayama announced that citizens should \"refrain as much as possible\" from visiting clusters of infected people in Hyogo and Osaka.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20200324/ddl/k33/040/397000c|date=24 March 2020|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u3000\u77e5\u4e8b\u30fb\u5e02\u9577\u300c\u62e1\u5927\u9632\u6b62\u3001\u5168\u529b\u6319\u3052\u308b\u300d\u3000\u5ca1\u5c71\uff16\uff10\u4ee3\u5973\u6027\u611f\u67d3\u3067\u3000\uff0f\u5ca1\u5c71|publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, more than 55,000 people flocked to a cauldron with the Olympic flame that was on display at Sendai Station in Sendai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/03/22/olympic-flame-in-japan-attracts-55000-despite-virus-fears}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Saitama and Gunma prefectures recorded their first deaths from the coronavirus, while 46 additional cases of infection were confirmed, including the first patient in Okayama Prefecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13237590|date=22 March 2020|title=First deaths in Saitama and Gunma due to new coronavirus|publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, according to the Japanese Health, Labour and Welfare Ministry, five deaths occurred.{{page needed|date=March 2020}} A [[K-1|K-1 Grand Prix]] [[martial art]] event was held despite authorities asking the organizers to shut it down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/newspaper/\uff13\u6708\uff12\uff13\u65e5\uff08\u6708\uff09\u767a\u884c-2/|date=March 23, 2020|title=\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u798d\u306e\u4e2d\u3067\u5f37\u884c\u958b\u50ac\u3000\uff2b\uff0d\uff11\u306f\uff2b\uff39\u3060\u3063\u305f\u306e\u304b}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Tokyo governor [[Yuriko Koike]] warned citizens that a lockdown might be necessary if infections were to surge in Tokyo as she urged people to cooperate to avoid a city-wide lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/24/national/tokyo-governor-urges-cooperation-avoid-city-lockdown/#.XnszRKnVKM8|title=As virus cases surge, Tokyo governor says lockdown may be only way to stem rise|website=[[Japan Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13240195|title=Koike warns of 'lockdown' option if infections surge in Tokyo|website=[[Asahi Shimbun]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-tokyo/governor-of-japans-capital-urges-cooperation-to-avoid-city-lockdown-idUSKBN21A18S|title=Governor of Japan's capital urges cooperation to avoid city lockdown|website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, MHLW officials announced 71 people tested positive,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13243134|title=Tokyo now the hot spot for virus infections with 171 cases|website=[[Asahi Shimbun]]}}</ref> including 41 cases in [[Tokyo]].<ref name=\"JT40Cases\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/25/national/science-health/tokyo-logs-40-coronavirus-cases/#.XnwlJ6nVKM8|title=Tokyo governor urges people to stay indoors over weekend as virus cases spike|website=[[Japan Times]]}}</ref> Governor Yuriko Koike held an emergency press conference in the late afternoon. She said that \"the current situation is a serious situation where the number of infected people may explode.\" Koike also asked \"if possible, work at home and refrain from going out at night as much as possible on weekdays.\" Koike asked people returning from abroad to refrain from going out for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200325/p2g/00m/0na/132000c|title=Tokyo residents asked to stay indoors at weekend due to coronavirus|website=[[The Mainichi]]}}</ref> The request from the governor appears to have punctured the relaxed mood in Tokyo. [[Panic buying]] began to trend on Twitter, with users posting pictures of empty shelves and lines outside supermarkets. At the [[Don Quijote (store)|Don Qujiote]] store in Nakameguro, customers flocked to grab instant noodles and canned goods immediately following Koike's late-evening speech.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-25/virus-cases-jump-in-tokyo-governor-koike-set-to-brief-press|title=Tokyo Edges Toward Tougher Approach A-s Virus Cases Spread|website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, several governors of the [[Greater Tokyo Area]], including Chiba, Kanagawa, Saitama, and Yamanashi, strongly urged residents to follow stay-at-home requests to prevent a surge in infections that could cause a \"critical phase\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020032600629/kanagawa-pref-to-also-issue-stay-at-home-request.html|date=Mar 26, 2020|title=Kanagawa Pref. to Also Issue Stay-at-Home Request|publisher=[[Jiji Press]]|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> In Tokyo, residents were asked to work from home and refrain from going out at night and on the weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13246749|date=26 March 2020|title=Prefectures urging residents to avoid travel to virus-hit Tokyo|publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, MHLW officials announced 112 people had tested positive in a single day, including three [[Hanshin Tigers]] professional baseball players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/sports/3-Hanshin-Tigers-players-test-positive-for-coronavirus|date=27 March 2020|title=3 Hanshin Tigers players test positive for coronavirus|website=[[The Japan Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020032700808/3-hanshin-tigers-players-test-positive-for-coronavirus.html|date=27 March 2020|title=3 Hanshin Tigers Players Test Positive for Coronavirus|website=[[Jiji Press]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Abe held an hour-long press briefing about the economic measures being prepared by the Japanese government<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-japan/tokyo-restricts-movement-to-combat-virus-some-folk-carry-on-as-usual-idUSKBN21F05Y?il=0|date=28 March 2020|title=Japan's Abe vows unprecedented stimulus as Tokyo coronavirus cases rise|website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/japan-to-extend-stimulus-on-unprecedented-scale-abe-says|date=28 March 2020|title=Japan Set for Biggest-Ever Stimulus to Battle Virus, Abe Says|website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]}}</ref> amid considerable concerns of an \"explosive spread of overflowing infections\", which was creating regional self-isolation requests around Japan, including in Tokyo, Osaka, Hyogo, and Aichi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/japan-pm-shinzo-abe-vows-unprecedented-stimulus-tokyo-coronavirus-cases-rise-by-daily|date=28 March 2020|title=Tokyo and Osaka at virtual standstill as PM Abe warns of explosive surge in coronavirus cases|website=The Strait Times}}</ref> Abe's wife became the centre of controversy when she was accused of attending a ''[[hanami]]'' party during the pandemic. Abe denied the claim and said she merely took pictures in front of some cherry trees after going to a restaurant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200328/p2a/00m/0dm/009000c|date=28 March 2020|title=PM Abe defends wife after claim she went to sakura party amid call for social distancing|website=[[The Mainichi]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, MHLW officials announced 194 people had tested positive for the virus, including 58 people at a facility for the disabled in [[T\u014dnosh\u014d]], [[Chiba Prefecture]], and 63 in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200329_25/|date=29 March 2020|title=Tokyo reports largest daily case total|website=[[NHK World-Japan]]}}</ref> However, a Tokyo municipal government official acknowledged by the end of the day that 63 people in the city tested positive for COVID-19 on 28 March and that a record number of 68 people tested positive on 29 March.<ref name=tokyolargest>{{cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/90242a1d5387-over-60-new-coronavirus-infections-confirmed-in-tokyo.html|title=Tokyo confirms 68 new coronavirus cases, record daily increase|publisher=Kyodo News|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> It was also revealed that Tokyo now had 430 confirmed cases of COVID-19, the largest among Japan's [[Prefectures of Japan|47 prefectures]].<ref name=tokyolargest />\n\nOn 30 March, it was announced that [[tarento]] and comedian [[Ken Shimura]] had died at the age of 70 from complications of a COVID-19 infection. This marked the first major death from the pandemic in Japan's entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u30b3\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u30f3\u306e\u5fd7\u6751\u3051\u3093\u3055\u3093\u6b7b\u53bb \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u611f\u67d3\u3067\u80ba\u708e\u767a\u75c7 |url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200330/k10012357011000.html |website=NHK\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/comedian-ken-shimura-japans-robin-williams-dies-coronavirus-1202895506/|title=Comedian Ken Shimura, 'Japan's Robin Williams', Dies Of Coronavirus|first=Tom|last=Grater|publisher=Deadline.com|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Shimura\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ken-shimura-dead-japanese-comedian-died-coronavirus-at-70-1287377|title=Japanese Comedian Ken Shimura Dies From Coronavirus at 70|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Fukuoka City announced confirmed cases in a woman in her 20s and her infant daughter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200330/k10012358671000.html?utm_int=detail_contents_news-related_001|date=30 March 2020|title=\u798f\u5ca1 \uff11\u6b73\u672a\u6e80\u306e\u5973\u5150\u3068\u6bcd\u89aa\u611f\u67d3\u78ba\u8a8d \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca|language=Japanese|publisher=[[NHK]]|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 30 March, Toyama prefecture announced its first case,<ref name=\"toyama1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200330/k10012358441000.html|title=\u5bcc\u5c71\u770c\u3067\u521d\u611f\u67d3 \u4eac\u7523\u5927\u5352\u696d\u795d\u8cc0\u4f1a\u306b\u53c2\u52a0\u306e20\u4ee3\u5973\u6027|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> and a Kyoto government official announced that the [[Kyoto Sangyo University]] had undergone \"a cluster of infections\"\u2014including two students who had recently returned from travel to Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jen.jiji.com/jc/eng?g=eco&k=2020033001060|title=More Coronavirus Cases Found among Kyoto Sangyo University Students|publisher=Jiji Press|date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/backstories/1007/ |title=Sounding the coronavirus alarm for Japan's youths &#124; NHK WORLD-JAPAN News |publisher=.nhk.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"Sangyo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200331/k10012358821000.html|title=\u5ca1\u5c71 \u4eac\u7523\u5927\u5352\u696d\u751f\u306e\u611f\u67d3\u78ba\u8a8d \u53cb\u4eba\u3068\u4f1a\u98df \u611f\u67d3\u306f\u770c\u5185\uff14\u4eba\u76ee|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nBy 31 March, calls were being made for Abe to declare a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200331/p2g/00m/0na/010000c|title=Calls grow for Japan PM Abe to declare state of emergency over virus|publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]}}</ref><ref name=\"tokyo brink\">{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200331_34/|title=Koike urges Abe to decide on emergency declaration|publisher=[[NHK World-Japan]]}}</ref> However, Abe and Chief Cabinet Secretary Suga denied that a state of emergency was immediately necessary.<ref name=\"imminent\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13259581|title=Abe, Suga flatly deny a state of emergency is imminent|publisher=[[The Asahi Shimbun]]}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n[[File:Shibuya Crossing 2020-04-19 (2).jpg|thumb|Few pedestrians in [[Shibuya Crossing]] during the state of emergency]]\nOn 3 April, Japan expanded its entry ban, effectively barring entrance to the country for visitors from 73 countries and regions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan to expand entry ban to 73 countries, regions amid virus spread|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200401/p2g/00m/0na/103000c|publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 7 April, Abe proclaimed a state of emergency from 8 April to 6 May for Tokyo and the prefectures of Kanagawa, Saitama, Chiba, Osaka, Hyogo and Fukuoka. He also said there would be no lockdown like in other countries, and that public transportation and other services needed to keep the economy and society going would be maintained as much as possible.<ref name=\"SevenPrefectures\">{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200407_43/|title=Abe declares state of emergency for 7 prefectures|date=April 7, 2020|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=|trans-title=|format=|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> This was the first emergency declaration in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200406_37/|title=Japan to declare emergency for 7 prefectures|date=2020-04-06|publisher=NHK|accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/5c77df980ac8-breaking-news-abe-to-declare-state-of-emergency-over-virus-govt-official.html|title=Japan PM Abe to declare state of emergency amid surge in virus infections|date=|publisher=English.kyodonews.net|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Abe also stated that the pandemic had created the nation's greatest economic crisis since the end of World War II.<ref name=\"416emergency\" /> \n\nOn 9 April, Kiminobu Okada (\u5ca1\u7530\u516c\u4f38), an executive of [[Mainichi Broadcasting System]] in Osaka, died due to coronavirus in Nishinomiya.<ref name=\"kouhou\">{{Cite press release|title=\u8a03\u5831|publisher=\u6bce\u65e5\u653e\u9001|date=2020-04-09|url=https://www.mbs.jp/kouhou/news/log/200409.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=\u5ca1\u7530\u516c\u4f38\u6c0f\u6b7b\u53bb \u6bce\u65e5\u653e\u9001\u53d6\u7de0\u5f79|newspaper=\u4f50\u8cc0\u65b0\u805eLiVE|date=2020-04-09|url=https://www.saga-s.co.jp/articles/-/510425|accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Narita International Airport]] closed one of its two runways on 12 April due to an 85 percent reduction in traffic caused by the virus.<ref>{{cite news|title=Narita airport to close runway as traffic plunges|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200410_27/|work=[[NHK World-Japan]]|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Intl. flights at Narita airport drop sharply|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200410_18/|work=[[NHK World-Japan]]|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA second wave of infections hit Hokkaido, prompting the prefectural government to declare a second state of emergency that closed schools and that asked residents to avoid non-essential trips.<ref name=\"npr_hokkaido\" />\n\nOn 16 April, the Japanese government expanded the state of emergency to include all 47 prefectures in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan's state of emergency extended nationwide | url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200417_01/ |date=17 April 2020|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=|trans-title=|format=|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> The government also announced a plan to give 100,000 yen to every registered resident of Japan.<ref>{{cite news|title=How to get the \u00a5100,000 coronavirus payout from the Japanese government|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/04/21/national/how-to-get-coronavirus-payout-japan/#.XqBe75lS-00|newspaper=[[The Japan Times]]|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, according to the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications]], 25 people died in a single day, the highest number of daily nationwide confirmed fatalities.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 21 April, former chairman of [[Omron]] Yoshio Tateishi (\u7acb\u77f3\u7fa9\u96c4) died due to COVID-19 in Kyoto, according to the Omron website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Obituaries/Yoshio-Tateishi-former-Omron-president-dies-of-coronavirus|date=21 April 2020|work=Nikkei Asian Review|title=Yoshio Tateishi, former Omron president, dies of coronavirus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/04/21/business/yoshio-tateishi-omron-president-dies-pneumonia-coronavirus/#.XqJyY4TVKM8|date=21 April 2020|work=The Japan Times|title=Yoshio Tateishi, former Omron president, dies of pneumonia linked to COVID-19}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, 29 persons nationwide were confirmed to have died, including [[Actress|actress]] [[Kumiko Okae]] (\u5ca1\u6c5f\u4e45\u7f8e\u5b50),  according to a JMIAC confirmed report.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200424_03/|date=23 April 2020|work=NHK World-Japan|title=Actress Okae Kumiko dies from coronavirus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/04/23/national/actress-kumiko-okae-dies-coronavirus/#.XqJ25oTVKM8|date=23 April 2020|work=JiJi Press (via The Japan Times)|title=Actress Kumiko Okae dies from coronavirus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/c67e2d11814f-japanese-actress-okae-dies-after-novel-coronavirus-infection.html|date=23 April 2020|work=Kyodo News|title=Japanese actress Kumiko Okae dies after novel coronavirus infection}}</ref>\nAccording to a National Police Agency of Japan confirmed report, 73 police officers had tested positive since February, and there were an additional 15 confirmed deaths from COVID-19 from March found in people who had died outside hospitals, mainly people who were [[Homelessness in Japan|homeless]] and had been tested posthumously.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}   \n\n<!-- \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+Confirmed Diagnosis Cases on March in Sample Region\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Date||colspan=\"2\"|Hokkaido||colspan=\"2\"|Gunma||colspan=\"2\"|Tochogi||colspan=\"2\"|Ibaraki||colspan=\"2\"|Chiba\n!colspan=\"2\"|Saitama||colspan=\"2\"|Tokyo||colspan=\"2\"|Kanagawa||colspan=\"2\"|Aichi||colspan=\"2\"|Kyoto||colspan=\"2'|Osaka||colspan=\"2\"|Hyogo||colspan=\"2\"|Fukuoka\n|-\n!Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total||Daily||Total\n|-\n|2020/03/01||2||72\n|-\n|2020/03/02||5||77\n|-\n|} -->\n\n==Government response==\n===Phase 1: Containment===\nThe initial response of the Japanese government to the COVID-19 outbreak was a policy of containment that focused on the repatriation of Japanese citizens from Wuhan, the point of origin of the pandemic, and the introduction of new border control regulations.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 24 January, Abe convened the Ministerial Meeting on Countermeasures Related to the Novel Coronavirus at the Prime Minister's Office with members of his Cabinet in response to a statement by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirming human-to-human transmission of the coronavirus. Abe announced that he would introduce appropriate countermeasures to the disease in coordination with the [[:ja:\u56fd\u7acb\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u7814\u7a76\u6240|National Institute of Infectious Diseases]] (NIID).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202001/_00024.html|title=Ministerial Meeting on Countermeasures Related to the Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, Abe designated the new coronavirus as an \"infectious disease\" under the {{Nihongo|[[:ja:\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306e\u4e88\u9632\u53ca\u3073\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306e\u60a3\u8005\u306b\u5bfe\u3059\u308b\u533b\u7642\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u6cd5\u5f8b|Infectious Diseases Control Law]]|\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306e\u4e88\u9632\u53ca\u3073\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306e\u60a3\u8005\u306b\u5bfe\u3059\u308b\u533b\u7642\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u6cd5\u5f8b}}, which allows the government to order patients with COVID-19 to undergo hospitalization. He also designated the disease as a \"quarantinable infectious disease\" under the Quarantine Act, which allows the government to quarantine people suspected of infection and order them to undergo diagnosis and treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ202001270041.html|title=Japan will label coronavirus as infectious disease to fight spread|website=The Asahi Shimbun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, Abe announced the establishment of the {{Nihongo|\"Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"|\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u672c\u90e8}}, which meets at the [[Prime Minister's Official Residence (Japan)|Prime Minister's Official Residence]] and is run by a task force led by [[:ja:\u5185\u95a3\u5371\u6a5f\u7ba1\u7406\u76e3|Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary for Crisis Management]] [[:ja:\u6c96\u7530\u82b3\u6a39|Okita Yoshiki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kantei.go.jp/jp/singi/novel_coronavirus/kanjikai/konkyo.pdf|script-title=zh:\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u672c\u90e8\u5e79\u4e8b\u4f1a\u306e\u69cb\u6210\u54e1\u306e\u5b98\u8077\u306e\u6307\u5b9a\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 |trans-title=On the Specification of the Official Positions of the Members of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters|last=|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202001/_00034.html|title=Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters|last=|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> The initial roster of the task force includes 36 high-ranking bureaucrats from several of the [[Ministries of Japan]]. The headquarters acts as the site of Abe's decision-making process on the country's virus countermeasures.\n\nOn 31 January, Abe announced during the second meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters that the government was prioritizing the repatriation of Japanese citizens from Hubei province. Officials negotiated with Chinese authorities to dispatch five chartered flights to Wuhan from 29 January to 17 February.<ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202001/_00037.html \"Second Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 31 January 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, Abe announced during the fourth meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters that he would enact restrictions to deny entry to foreign citizens who had visited Hubei province within 14 days and to those with a Chinese passport issued by Hubei province.<ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00001.html \"Fourth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 1 February 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 5 February, Abe announced that he would invoke the Quarantine Act to place the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' under quarantine in [[Yokohama]]. Quarantine officers were dispatched to the ship to prevent the disembarkation of crew and passengers, and to escort infected patients to medical facilities.<ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00006.html \"Fifth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 5 February 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 6 February, Abe invoked the Immigration Control and Refugee Act to deny entry to the cruise ship ''[[MS Westerdam]]'' from Hong Kong after one of its passengers tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>[Sixth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters \"Sixth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\", Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 6 February 2020]</ref>\n\n===Reinforcement of medical service system===\n[[File:Members of the Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting and Ministers cropped 2 Members of the Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting and Ministers 20200216.jpg|thumb|250px|Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] convening the first Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting on 16 February 2020|alt=]]\n\nAfter the COVID-19 outbreak on the cruise ship ''Diamond Princess'', the Japanese government shifted its focus from a containment policy to a prevention and treatment one because it anticipated rising numbers of community spreads within Japan. This policy prioritized the creation of a COVID-19 testing and consultation system based on the National Institute of Infectious Diseases (NIID) and the government's existing 83 municipal and prefectural public health institutions that is separate from the civilian hospital system.  The new system handles the transfer of COVID-19 patients to mainstream medical facilities to facilitate patient flow, triage, and the management of limited testing kits on their behalf to prevent a rush of infected and uninfected patients from overwhelming healthcare providers and transmitting diseases to them.  By regulating COVID-19 testing at the national level, the Abe Administration integrated the activities of the national government, the local governments, medical professionals, business operators, and the public in treating the disease.\n\nOn 1 February, the [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare]] instructed the municipal and prefectural governments to establish specialized COVID-19 consultation centres and outpatient wards at their local public health facilities by the first half of the month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20200203/k00/00m/040/227000c|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\u300c\u5e30\u56fd\u8005\u30fb\u63a5\u89e6\u8005\u76f8\u8ac7\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u300d\u8a2d\u7f6e\u3078 \u5c02\u9580\u5916\u6765\u3078\u306e\u53d7\u8a3a\u3092\u4fc3\u3059|last=|first=|date=2020-02-03|work=[[Mainichi]] |language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>  Such wards would provide medical examinations and testing for suspected carriers of the disease to protect general hospitals from infection.\n\nOn 5 February, PM Abe announced during the Fifth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters that the government would begin preparations to strengthen COVID-19 testing capabilities at the NIID and 83 municipal and prefectural public health institutions that are designated by the government as official testing sites.  Without any uniform diagnosis kit for the disease, the government has relied on [[polymerase chain reaction]] (PCR) tests to check for infections. As few mainstream medical facilities in Japan had the ability to conduct PCR tests, Abe also promised to increase the number of institutions with such kits, including universities and private companies <ref>{{cite web|url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00006.html|title=Fifth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February, PM Abe announced during the Seventh Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Headquarters that the government would expand the scope of COVID-19 testing to include patients with symptoms based on the discretion of local governments.  Previously, testing was restricted to those with a history of travelling to Hubei Province.<ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00016.html \"Seventh Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 12 February 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/13135381|title=Japan, alarmed by new cases, to expand, speed up coronavirus tests|website=The Asahi Shimbun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\u3000On the same day, the Ministry of Health and NIID also contracted SRL Inc to handle PCR clinical laboratory testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ssl4.eir-parts.net/doc/4544/tdnet/1794814/00.pdf|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u691c\u67fb\u306e\u53d7\u8a17\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066|last=SRL|date=12 February 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  Since then, the government has partnered with several more private companies to expand laboratory testing capabilities and to work towards the development of a rapid testing kit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Corporate-Japan-rushes-to-devise-quick-coronavirus-tests|title=Corporate Japan rushes to devise quick coronavirus tests|website=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, PM Abe introduced the Japanese government's coronavirus consultation system to coordinate medical testing and response with the public. The [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare]] worked with local governments to establish 536 {{Nihongo|[[:ja:\u5e30\u56fd\u8005\u30fb\u63a5\u89e6\u8005\u76f8\u8ac7\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc|consultation centres]]|\u5e30\u56fd\u8005\u30fb\u63a5\u89e6\u8005\u76f8\u8ac7\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc}} that covered every prefecture within the country to provide concerned citizens with instructions on how to receive COVID-19 testing and treatment. The general public needs to contact a consultation centre by phone to get tested at one of the government's {{Nihongo|specialized outpatient wards|\u5e30\u56fd\u8005\u30fb\u63a5\u89e6\u8005\u5916\u6765}}.<ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00024.html \"Ninth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 14 February 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/seisakunitsuite/bunya/kenkou_iryou/covid19-kikokusyasessyokusya.html|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u5e30\u56fd\u8005\u30fb\u63a5\u89e6\u8005\u76f8\u8ac7\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc|last=|first=|date=February 13, 2020|website=Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, PM Abe convened the government's first {{Nihongo|Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting|\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u5c02\u9580\u5bb6\u4f1a\u8b70}} at the Prime Minister's Office to draft national guidelines for COVID-19 testing and treatment.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kantei.go.jp/jp/singi/novel_coronavirus/senmonkakaigi/konkyo.pdf|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u5c02\u9580\u5bb6\u4f1a\u8b70\u306e\u958b\u50ac\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 (On the Opening of the First Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting)|last=|first=|date=14 February 2020|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>  The meeting was chaired by Dr. [[:ja:\u8107\u7530\u9686\u5b57|Wakita Takaji]], Director of the NIID, who brought together ten public health experts and medical professionals from across Japan to coordinate a response to the virus with PM Abe and the government's coronavirus task force in a roundtable format. The main concern of the Japanese medical establishment was an overcrowding of hospitals by uninfected patients with light cold symptoms who believed that they had COVID-19. Medical representatives claimed that such a panic would strain medical resources and risk exposing those uninfected patients to the disease itself.<ref>Sait\u014d, Katsuhisa (19 February 2020) [https://www.nippon.com/en/news/l00267/early-stage-of-a-japan-outbreak-the-policies-needed-to-support-coronavirus-patients.html \"Early Stage of a Japan Outbreak: The Policies Needed to Support Coronavirus Patients\"]. Nippon.com.</ref><ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00022.html \"First Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 19 February 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 17 February, the Ministry of Health released its {{Nihongo|consultation guidelines|\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u306e\u76f8\u8ac7\u30fb\u53d7\u8a3a\u306e\u76ee\u5b89\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066}} to each of the municipal and prefectural governments and their public health centres.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/10900000/000596978.pdf|script-title=ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u306e\u76f8\u8ac7\u30fb\u53d7\u8a3a\u306e\u76ee\u5b89\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 (Criterion for Consultation and Medical Examination in regard to the Novel Coronavirus Disease)|last=|first=|date=17 February 2020|website=Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The document instructs doctors and public health nurses who staff the consultation centres to limit consultations to people with the following conditions: (1) cold symptoms and a fever of at least 37.5 Celsius for over four days while taking antipyretic medication; and (2) extreme fatigue and breathing difficulties.  The elderly, people with pre-existing conditions, and pregnant women with cold symptoms can receive consultation if they have had them for two days.  The guidelines also note that people who are dissatisfied with their consultation results can visit one of the specialized outpatient wards for further talks.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 22 February, Health Minister Kato announced that the Japanese government was looking into the use of [[favipiravir]], an anti-influenza medication developed by [[Fujifilm]], to treat patients with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Joshua Hunt |url=https://www.wired.com/story/japan-is-racing-to-test-a-drug-to-treat-covid-19/ |title=Japan Is Racing to Test Favipiravir, a Drug to Treat Covid-19 |journal=WIRED |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/22/national/science-health/flu-drug-avigan-coronavirus/#.Xo1vC1NKgUE |title=Japan might approve anti-flu drug Avigan to treat coronavirus patients |newspaper=The Japan Times Online |publisher=The Japan Times |date=2020-02-22 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The company responded by increasing production of the drug, providing technical support to clinical researchers, and distributing the drug to hospitals where its use has been approved by the government for emergency purposes.  The first clinical trial is expected to conclude in June.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Phase 2: Mitigation===\n[[File:Japanese Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare and Objective of Novel Coronavirus Countermeasure.pdf|thumb|The objective of the Japanese government's basic policies for control is to \"flatten the curve\".|alt=]]\nOn 25 February, the Abe Administration introduced the \"Basic Policies for Novel Coronavirus Disease Control\" ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u306e\u57fa\u672c\u65b9\u91dd) to act as the government's uniform basic policy on COVID-19 control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kantei.go.jp/jp/singi/novel_coronavirus/th_siryou/kihonhousin.pdf|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u306e\u57fa\u672c\u65b9\u91dd (Basic Policies for Novel Coronavirus Disease Control)|last=|first=|date=25 February 2020|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> After a spike of infections in Italy, Iran, and South Korea, PM Abe decided that the government's disease countermeasures would prioritize the prevention of large-scale clusters in Japan. This includes the government's controversial requests to suspend such large-scale gatherings as community events and school operations, as well as its policy to limit patients with light cold symptoms from visiting medical facilities to prevent them from overwhelming hospital resources.<ref>[https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/10200000/000603611.pdf \"Basic Policies for Novel Coronavirus Disease Control\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 25 February 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 23 February, PM Abe instructed the government's coronavirus task force to quickly draft a comprehensive basic policy.<ref>[https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020022300422/abe-orders-basic-coronavirus-policy-with-eye-on-epidemic.html?cx_recs_click=true \"Abe Orders Basic Coronavirus Policy with Eye on Epidemic\"]. Nippon.com, 23 February 2020</ref> Health Minister [[Katsunobu Kato]] reconvened the medical experts from the first Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting on 24 February to draft this policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020022400554/japanese-experts-discuss-basic-coronavirus-policy.html|title=Japanese Experts Discuss Basic Coronavirus Policy|date=24 February 2020|website=nippon.com|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> During the meeting, the medical establishment presented its policy recommendations in the form of a views report ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u306e\u57fa\u672c\u65b9\u91dd\u306e\u5177\u4f53\u5316\u306b\u5411\u3051\u305f\u898b\u89e3), concluding that the most important objective of PM Abe's basic policy must be the prevention of large-scale disease clusters and a decrease in the outbreak and death of patients with severe symptoms. They stated that it is not possible for the government to prevent the spread of COVID-19 in Japan on a person-to-person basis, but that there is a possibility that it can regulate the overall speed of infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/seisakunitsuite/newpage_00006.html|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u306e\u57fa\u672c\u65b9\u91dd\u306e\u5177\u4f53\u5316\u306b\u5411\u3051\u305f\u898b\u89e3 (Opinion on the Realization of Basic Policies for Novel Coronavirus Disease Control)|last=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u5c02\u9580\u5bb6\u4f1a\u8b70 (Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting)|date=February 24, 2020|website=Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>&nbsp; They cited the next week or two as a \"critical moment\" on whether the country would experience a large cluster that could result in the collapse of the medical system and socio-economic chaos. After reviewing and discussing the existing data on the disease, the committee stated that universal PCR testing was impossible due to a shortage of testing facilities and providers, and recommended that the government instead limit the application of available test kits to patients that are at a high risk of complications in order to stockpile for a large cluster.&nbsp; Participants also noted that Japan's medical facilities are vulnerable to \"chaos,\" elaborating that several of the hospital beds and resources in the Tokyo area are already preoccupied with caring for the surge of 700 infected patients from the ''Diamond Princess''. They reiterated their warning that a rush of alarmed uninfected outpatients with light symptoms of the disease could overwhelm hospitals and turn waiting rooms into \"breeding grounds\" of COVID-19.<ref name=\"nippon1\">[https://www.nippon.com/en/news/l00269/coronavirus-basic-policy-impacts-japan%e2%80%99s-health-education-systems.html?cx_recs_click=true \"Coronavirus Basic Policy Impacts Japan\u2019s Health, Education Systems\"]. Nippon.com, 2 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 25 February, the Abe Administration adopted the \"Basic Policies for Novel Coronavirus Disease Control\" based on the advice that it received from the Expert Meeting.\n\nFirst, the new policies advised local medical institutions that it is better for people with lighter, cold-like symptoms to rely on bed rest at home, rather than seeking medical help from clinics or hospitals. The policy also recommends people at a higher risk of infection -including the elderly and patients with pre-existing conditions \u2013 to avoid hospital visits for such non-treatment purposes as completing prescription orders by letting them fill the forms over the telephone instead of in person.<ref name=\"nippon1\" />\n\nSecond, the new policies allow general medical facilities in areas of a rapid COVID-19 outbreak to accept patients suspected of infection. Before this, patients could only get tested at specialized clinics after making an appointment with consultation centres to prevent the transmission of the disease. Government officials revised the previous policy after acknowledging that such specialized institutions would be overwhelmed during a large cluster.\n\nThird, the policy asks those with any cold symptoms to take time off from work and avoid leaving their homes. Government officials urged companies to let employees work from home and commute at off-peak hours. The Japanese government also made an official request to local governments and businesses to cancel large-scale events.\n\nOn 27 February, PM Abe requested the closures of all schools from 2 March to the end of spring vacations, which usually conclude in early April. The next day, the Japanese government announced plans to create a fund to help companies subsidize workers who need to take days off to look after their children while schools are closed.<ref>[https://business.financialpost.com/pmn/business-pmn/japan-to-create-fund-to-subsidize-parents-during-school-closure-nikkei \"Japan to create fund to subsidize parents during school closure-Nikkei\"]. ''Financial Post'', 28 February 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, the Japanese government also announced plans to expand the national health insurance system so that it covers COVID-19 tests.<ref>[https://www.nippon.com/en/news/ntv20200227002/coronavirus-national-health-insurance-to-cover-virus-test.html?cx_recs_click=true Coronavirus: National Health Insurance to Cover Virus Test]. Nippon.com, 27 February 2020</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the Ministry of Health reconvened the Expert Meeting after the two week \"critical moment.\" The panel of medical experts concluded that Japan was currently not on track to experience a large-scale cluster, but stated that there is a two-week time lag in analysing COVID-19 trends and that the country would continue to see more infections. Consequently, the participants asked the government to remain vigilant in quickly identifying and containing smaller clusters. With more COVID-19 outbreaks around the world, the panel also proposed that new infections from abroad could initiate a \"second wave\" of the disease in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/10900000/000608425.pdf|title=Views on the Novel Coronavirus Disease Control (Summary Version)|last=The Government of Japan, Expert Meeting on the Novel Coronavirus Disease Control|date=9 March 2020|publisher=Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (in English)|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/10900000/000606000.pdf|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u306e\u898b\u89e3|last=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u5bfe\u7b56\u5c02\u9580\u5bb6\u4f1a\u8b70|language=ja|date=9 March 2020|publisher=Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the Health Ministry published a disease forecast of each prefecture and instructed their local governments to prepare their hospitals to accommodate its patient estimates. It predicts that the virus peak of each prefecture will occur three months after their first reported case of local transmission. The Ministry estimates that during its peak, Tokyo will see 45,400 outpatients and 20,500 inpatients per day, of whom 700 will be in severe condition. For [[Hokkaido]], the figure is 18,300 outpatients and 10,200 inpatients daily, of whom about 340 will be in severe condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/8aafa8e3636c-local-govts-urged-to-prepare-for-peak-of-coronavirus-infections.html|title=Japan local gov'ts urged to prepare for peak of coronavirus infections|last=NEWS|first=KYODO|website=Kyodo News+|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== State of Emergency declaration ===\n[[File:Broadcast message asking people to stay home during Covid19 outbreak.webm|thumb|Broadcast message asking people to stay home in Tokyo]]To provide a stronger legal basis for its COVID-19 countermeasures, the National Diet passed an amendment to the \"Special Measures Act to Counter New Types of Influenza of 2012\" ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: [[:ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30a4\u30f3\u30d5\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b6\u7b49\u5bfe\u7b56\u7279\u5225\u63aa\u7f6e\u6cd5|\u65b0\u578b\u30a4\u30f3\u30d5\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b6\u7b49\u5bfe\u7b56\u7279\u5225\u63aa\u7f6e\u6cd5]]) on 13 March.  The new act allows the Prime Minister to declare a \"state of emergency\" in specific areas where COVID-19 poses a grave threat to the lives and economic livelihood of residents.  During such a period, governors of affected areas will receive the following powers: (1) to instruct residents to avoid unnecessary outings unless they are workers in such essential services as health care and public transportation; (2) to restrict the use or request the temporary closure of businesses and facilities - including schools, social welfare facilities, theatres, music venues and sports stadiums; (3) to expropriate private land and buildings for the purpose of erecting new hospitals; and (4) to requisition medical supplies and food from companies that refuse to sell them, punish those that hoard or do not comply, and force firms to help transport emergency goods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/5c77df980ac8-breaking-news-abe-to-declare-state-of-emergency-over-virus-govt-official.html|title=Japan PM Abe to declare state of emergency amid surge in virus infections|last=NEWS|first=KYODO|website=Kyodo News+|access-date=6 April 2020|publisher=Kyodo News}}</ref>\n\nUnder the law, the Japanese government does not have the authority enforce citywide lockdowns.  Apart from individual quarantine measures, officials cannot restrict the movement of people in order to contain the virus. Consequently, compliance with government requests to restrict movements is based on \"asking for public cooperation to \u2018protect people\u2019s lives\u2019 and minimize further damage to [the economy]\".<ref>[https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/01/national/japan-coronavirus-outbreak/#.XlupkCFKiUk Tomohiro Osaki \"How far can Japan go to curb the coronavirus outbreak? Not as far as you may think]. ''The Japan Times'', 1 March 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 5 February, the Abe Administration's coronavirus task force initiated political debate on the introduction of emergency measures to combat the COVID-19 outbreak a day after the British cruise ship ''Diamond Princess'' was asked to quarantine. Initial debate focused on constitutional reform due to the task force's apprehension that the Japanese Constitution may restrict the government's ability to enact such compulsory measures as quarantines on the grounds that it violated human rights.  After lawmakers representing almost all of the major political parties \u2013 including the [[Liberal Democratic Party]], [[Constitutional Democratic Party of Japan]], and [[Democratic Party for the People]] \u2013 voiced their strong opposition towards this proposal and asserted that the Constitution allowed for emergency measures, the Abe Administration moved forward with legislative reform instead.<ref>[https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/05/national/japan-lawmakers-coronavirus-crisis-state-of-emergency-clause-rights/#.XmFZMpNKgUE \"Lawmakers slammed for using coronavirus to justify emergency clause for Japan's Constitution, curbing rights\"]. ''The Japan Times'', 5 February 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Prime Minister Abe introduced a draft amendment to the \"Special Measures Act to Counter New Types of Influenza of 2012\" so that the law's emergency measures for an influenza outbreak would include COVID-19 within its purview. He met separately with the heads of five opposition parties on 4 March to promote a \"united front\" in passing the reforms.  \n\nOn 13 March, the National Diet passed the revisions, which are effective for the next two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/57cfa56d5ecc-urgent-japans-diet-gives-abe-power-to-declare-emergency-amid-viral-fears.html|title=Japan's Diet gives Abe power to declare emergency amid viral fears|last=NEWS|first=KYODO|website=Kyodo News+|publisher=Kyodo News|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200305/p2a/00m/0fp/011000c Revised influenza law to allow Japan PM to declare state of emergency over coronavirus]. ''The Mainichi'', 5 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced that the daily number of confirmed cases in Tokyo increased from 17 to 41 cases compared to the day before.<ref name=\"JT40Cases\" /> Tokyo Governor [[Yuriko Koike]] held an emergency press conference in the late afternoon, stating that \"the current situation is a serious situation where the number of infected people may explode.\" She requested residents to refrain from nonessential outings during the upcoming weekend.\n\nOn 26 March, the Ministry of Health reconvened the Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting to review the new data. The panel of medical experts concluded that there was a \"high probability of an expansion of infections\" within the country due to an increase in the number of infected patients returning from Europe and the United States between 11 March and 23 March.<ref name=\"ExpertMeeting\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/10900000/000620826.pdf|title=Expert Meeting on Control of the Novel Coronavirus Disease Control|publisher=Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|date=1 April 2020|website=mhlw.go.jp|url-status=live|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> In response to the statement, PM Abe instructed Economic Policy Minister [[Yasutoshi Nishimura]] to establish a special government task force to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sugiyama|first=Satoshi|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/26/national/science-health/japan-coronavirus-task-force/|title=Japan coronavirus task force may set stage for state of emergency|date=26 March 2020|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=17 April 2020|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>  The move cleared a prerequisite toward declaring a state of emergency because any request for one by the Prime Minister would have to be approved by such a task force under the revised law.\n\nOn 30 March, Governor Koike requested residents to refrain from nonessential outings for the next two weeks until 12 April due to a continued increase in infections in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/national/Koike-calls-for-fewer-outings-says-state-of-emergency-up-to-PM|title=Koike calls for fewer outings; says state of emergency up to PM|work=Japan Today|language=en|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> During a press conference held by the [[Japan Medical Association]] that same day, [[:ja:\u91dc\u8422\u654f|Kamayachi Satoshi]] of the government's panel of medical experts stated that his fellow panelists were divided over whether PM Abe should declare a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/ce4960a6b1cc-calls-grow-for-japan-pm-to-declare-state-of-emergency-over-virus.html|title=Calls grow for Japan PM to declare state of emergency over virus|last=NEWS|first=KYODO|website=Kyodo News+|publisher=Kyodo News|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health reconvened the Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting to assess the current COVID-19 situation in Japan.<ref name=\"ExpertMeeting\" /> The medical experts discussed the data and concluded that although such urban areas as Tokyo and Osaka were witnessing a rapid increase in infection rates, they were not on a trajectory to experience a large-scale cluster seen in Europe and the United States.  Experts were still alarmed that infected patients could overwhelm the medical service system before an explosive spread of the virus as COVID-19 designated hospitals in major cities reached near capacity.  They requested the government to secure more hospital beds for patients and transfer those with mild or no symptoms to outside housing facilities.\n\nOn 2 April, the Ministry of Health issued a notice that urged non-critical COVID-19 patients to move out of hospitals and stay at home or at facilities designated by local governments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Japan-s-cities-scramble-to-move-mild-coronavirus-patients-to-hotels|title=Japan's cities scramble to move mild coronavirus patients to hotels|website=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en-GB|access-date=17 April 2020|publisher=Nihon Keizai Shimbun}}</ref> Prefectural governors across the country began arranging accommodations for such patients through hotel operators and dormitories and issued official requests to the [[Japan Self-Defense Forces|Japan Self-Defense Force]] for transportation services.\n\nOn 3 April, Professor Nishiura Hiroshi of the Ministry of Health's Cluster Response Team presented the initial findings of his COVID-19 [[Mathematical modelling of infectious disease|epidemiological models]] to the public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200403_18/|title=Expert: 80% less contact can stop explosive spread {{!}} NHK WORLD-JAPAN News|website=NHK WORLD|language=en|access-date=17 April 2020|publisher=NHK}}</ref> He concluded that the government could prevent an explosive spread of the virus in Japan if it adopted strict restrictions on outings that reduced social interactions by 80 per cent, while such a spread would occur if the government adopted no measures or reduced social interactions by 20 per cent. Nishiura added that Tokyo was about 10 days to two weeks away from a large-scale outbreak.\n\nOn 6 April, PM Abe announced that he would submit a request to declare a state of emergency on the next day at the earliest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202004/_00006.html|title=26th Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters (The Prime Minister in Action) {{!}} Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|website=japan.kantei.go.jp|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, PM Abe proclaimed a one-month state of emergency from 8 April to 6 May for Tokyo and the prefectures of Kanagawa, Saitama, Chiba, Osaka, Hyogo and Fukuoka.<ref name=\"SevenPrefectures2\">{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200407_43/|title=Abe declares state of emergency for 7 prefectures|date=7 April 2020|publisher=[[NHK]]|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> He stated that the number of patients would peak in two weeks if the number of person-to-person contact was reduced by 70 to 80 per cent, and urged the public to stay at home to achieve this goal over the next month.\n\nOn 10 April, Governor Koike announced closure requests for six categories of businesses in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200410_26/|title=Tokyo issues closure requests for 6 categories {{!}} NHK WORLD-JAPAN News|website=NHK WORLD|access-date=17 April 2020|publisher=NHK}}</ref>  They include amusement facilities, universities and cram schools, sports and recreation facilities, theatres, event and exhibition venues. and commercial facilities.  She also asked restaurants to limit opening hours between 5 a.m. and 8 p.m. and stop serving alcohol at 7 p.m. The request was to take effect on 12 April and promised government subsidies for businesses that cooperated with it.\n\nOn 11 April, Professor Nishiura presented the remaining findings of his COVID-19 epidemiological models.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO57961860R10C20A4CZ8000/|title=\u300c\u63a5\u89e67\u5272\u6e1b\u300d\u3067\u306f\u53ce\u675f\u307e\u3067\u9577\u671f\u5316 \u5317\u5927\u6559\u6388\u304c\u8b66\u9418|publisher=Nihon Keizai Shimbun|language=ja|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.tbs.co.jp/newseye/tbs_newseye3954230.html|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u611f\u67d3\u62e1\u5927\u3001\u63a5\u89e6\uff16\u5272\u6e1b\u3067\u3082\u611f\u67d3\u8005\u6570\u6e1b\u3089\u305a|website=TBS NEWS|language=ja|publisher=Tokyo Broadcasting System|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> He determined that reducing social interactions by 80 per cent would decrease the COVID-19 infection rate to a manageable level in 15 days; 70 per cent in 34 days; 65 per cent in 70 days; and 50 per cent in 3 months. Any rate below 60 percent would result in an increase in the number of cases.\n\nOn 16 April the declaration made on 8 April was expanded upon to include every prefecture in the country.<ref name=\"416emergency\"/>\n\n=== Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting ===\nOn 16 February, PM Abe convened the Novel Coronavirus Expert Meeting to incorporate members of the Japanese medical community into his decision-making process.<ref name=\":4\" /> The panel acts as the main medical advisory body of the Japanese government during the COVID-19 crisis.\n\n'''Chair'''\n\n* [[:ja:\u8107\u7530\u9686\u5b57|Wakita Takaji]] (Director-General of the [[:ja:\u56fd\u7acb\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u7814\u7a76\u6240|National Institute of Infectious Diseases]])\n\n'''Vice Chair'''\n\n* [[Shigeru Omi|Omi Shigeru]] (President of the [[:ja:\u5730\u57df\u533b\u7642\u6a5f\u80fd\u63a8\u9032\u6a5f\u69cb|Japan Community Health Care Organization]])\n\n'''Members'''\n\n* [[:ja:\u5ca1\u90e8\u4fe1\u5f66|Okabe Nobuhiko]] (Director of the Kawasaki Municipal Institute of Public Health)\n* [[:ja:\u62bc\u8c37\u4ec1|Oshitani Hitoshi]] (Professor of Virology at [[Tohoku University]])\n* [[:ja:\u91dc\u8422\u654f|Kamayachi Satoshi]] (Executive Board Member of the [[Japan Medical Association]])\n* [[Yoshihiro Kawaoka|Kawaoka Yoshihiro]] (Professor of Virology at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin-Madison]] and [[University of Tokyo]])\n* [[:ja:\u5ddd\u540d\u660e\u5f66|Kawana Akihiko]] (Professor of Internal Medicine at the [[National Defense Medical College]])\n* [[:ja:\u9234\u6728\u57fa|Suzuki Motoi]] (Director of the NIID Center of Infectious Disease Epidemiology)\n* [[:ja:\u8218\u7530\u4e00\u535a|Tateda Kazuhiro]] (Professor of Microbiology and Infectious Disease at [[Toho University]])\n* [[:ja:\u4e2d\u5c71\u3072\u3068\u307f|Nakayama Hitomi]] (Lawyer at the Kasumigaseki-Sogo Law Offices)\n* [[:ja:\u6b66\u85e4\u9999\u7e54|Muto Kaori]] (Professor of Cultural and Human Information Studies at the University of Tokyo)\n* [[:ja:\u5409\u7530\u6b63\u6a39 (\u533b\u5b66\u8005)|Yoshida Masaki]] (Professor of Internal Medicine at [[Jikei University School of Medicine]])\n\n=== Cluster countermeasures ===\n[[File:Japanese Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare \"Three Cs\".pdf|thumb|The Japanese government's COVID-19 countermeasures include public service announcements to avoid the \"Three Cs\".]]\nOn 25 February, the [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare]] established a \"Cluster Response Section\" ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u5bfe\u7b56\u73ed) in accordance to the Basic Policies for Novel Coronavirus Disease Control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/newpage_09743.html|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9 \u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u5bfe\u7b56\u73ed\u306e\u8a2d\u7f6e\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066|publisher=Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|language=ja|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>  The purpose of the new section is to quickly identify and contain small-scale clusters of COVID-19 infections before they turn into large-scale ones.  It is led by university professors [[:ja:\u62bc\u8c37\u4ec1|Oshitani Hitoshi]] and Nishiura Hiroshi and consists of a [[Contact tracing|contact trace]] team and a surveillance team from the [[:ja:\u56fd\u7acb\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u7814\u7a76\u6240|National Institute of Infectious Diseases]] (NIID), a data analysis team from [[Hokkaido University]], a risk management team from [[Tohoku University]], and an administration team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/10906000/000599837.pdf|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\u3000\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u5bfe\u7b56\u306b\u3088\u308b\u611f\u67d3\u62e1\u5927\u9632\u6b62|date=25 February 2020|publisher=Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|language=ja|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>  Whenever a local government determines the existence of a cluster from hospital reports, the Ministry of Health dispatches the Section to that area to conduct an epidemiological survey and contact tracing. After the teams determine the original source of infection, the Ministry and local government officials enact countermeasures to locate, test, and place under medical surveillance anybody who may have come into contact with an infected person. They can also file requests to suspend infected businesses or restrict events from taking place there.\n\nOn 15 March, the Ministry of Health reported fifteen COVID-19 clusters in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO56817600V10C20A3CE0000/|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u3001\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u5168\u56fd15\u30ab\u6240 \u539a\u52b4\u7701\u304c\u5730\u56f3\u516c\u8868|publisher=Nihon Keizai Shimbun|language=ja|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>  The largest cluster involves more than 80 people across four [[Live house|live music clubs]] in [[Osaka]] from concerts held in mid-February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/japan-identifies-15-clusters-as-covid-19-cases-mount|title=Japan identifies 15 clusters as Covid-19 cases mount|last=Sim|first=Walter|date=16 March 2020|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Another cluster of 50 people occurred at an elderly day care centre in [[Nagoya]] in early March, which resulted in 12 deaths.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-japan-nagoya-idUSKBN2140MC|title=Coronavirus cluster in Japan's Nagoya tied to elderly day care center|date=17 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Government support measures===\nOn 12 February, PM Abe announced during the Eighth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters that the government would secure a total of 500 billion yen for emergency lending and loan guarantees to small and medium enterprises affected by the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202002/_00019.html Eighth Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 12 February 2020.</ref> He also declared that his Cabinet would set aside 15.3 billion yen from contingency funds to facilitate the donation of isolated virus samples to relevant research institutions across the globe.\n\nOn 1 March, PM Abe evoked the Act on Emergency Measures for Stabilizing Living Conditions of the Public to regulate the sale and distribution of facial masks in Hokkaido.  Under this policy, the Japanese government instructed manufactures to sell facial masks directly to the government, which would then deliver it to residents.<ref>[https://japan.kantei.go.jp/98_abe/actions/202003/_00001.html \"16th Meeting of the Novel Coronavirus Response Headquarters\"]. Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet, 1 March 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, the Japanese government announced that it is organizing an emergency package by using a 270 billion yen ($2.5 billion) reserve fund for the current fiscal year through March to contain the virus and minimize its impact on the economy.\n\n===Controversies and criticisms===\n{{See also|Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Japanese government}}\nFrom 17 February, [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare]] asked people who have a fever over 37.5&deg;C for more than 4 days or those who have recognized strong helplessness and difficulty breathing  severer than such conditions for influenza are necessary to find and consult with the coronavirus-related 'Return and Contact Consultation Centre' installed in local governments around the country before get tested for novel coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/yjj2020021701007/people-with-fever-for-4-days-asked-to-seek-advice-on-coronavirus.html|date=17 February 2020|title=People with Fever for 4 Days Asked to Seek Advice on Coronavirus|language=English|publisher=[[Jiji Press]]|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/5908513a2660-abe-urges-people-with-cold-like-symptoms-to-avoid-work-school.html|date=18 February 2020|title=Japan PM Abe urges people with cold-like symptoms to avoid work, school|language=English|publisher=[[Kyodo News]]|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> However, some media outlets assert that restrictive and deliberate standards would rather delay response and create a socially loose atmosphere, leading to the spread of the disease, which could later lead to the collapse of the health care system and the medically protected regional community.<ref name=\"NYT-20FEB29-TestConstraints\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/coronavirus/japans-virus-success-has-puzzled-the-world-is-its-luck-running-out/ar-BB11L62Y|date=26 March 2020 |title=Japan's Virus Success Has Puzzled the World. Is Its Luck Running Out?|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late February, several Japanese media outlets reported that there were people with fever or other symptoms who could not be tested through the consultation centre system and had become \"test refugees\" ({{lang-ja|\u691c\u67fb\u96e3\u6c11}}).<ref>{{cite news |last1={{lang|ja|\u95a2\u897f\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u653e\u9001}} |first1=KTV |script-title=ja:\u300c\u691c\u67fb\u3067\u304d\u306a\u3044\u300d\u4e00\u822c\u306e\u533b\u7642\u6a5f\u95a2\u3082\u56f0\u60d1 \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9 |url=https://www.ktv.jp/news/articles/04378cc2988240b1816c75aead5dfa3c.html |work=ktv.jp |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u75c5\u96624\u56de...\u3067\u3082\u691c\u67fb\u3067\u304d\u305a \u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e \u4e0d\u5b89\u306e\u58f0 |url=https://www.fnn.jp/posts/00432792CX/202002261149_CX_CX |work=FNN.jp |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u300c\u767a\u71b1 \u7d9a\u3044\u3066\u308b\u306e\u306b\u30fb\u30fb\u30fb\u300d\"\u691c\u67fb\u96e3\u6c11\"\u306e\u4e0d\u5b89 |url=https://news.tbs.co.jp/newseye/tbs_newseye3915821.html |work=TBS NEWS |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u65b0\u578b\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u300c\u691c\u67fb\u53d7\u3051\u3089\u308c\u305a\u300d\u306e\u58f0\u76f8\u6b21\u3050 \u3044\u307e\u73fe\u5834\u3067\u306f |url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200227/k10012304321000.html |work=NHK|language=ja}}</ref> Some of these cases involved patients with severe pneumonia.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u691c\u67fb\u3067\u304d\u306a\u3044 \u75c5\u9662\u60b2\u9cf4 |url=https://news.tbs.co.jp/newseye/tbs_newseye3911070.html |work=TBS NEWS |language=ja |title=\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u691c\u67fb\u3067\u304d\u306a\u3044 \u75c5\u9662\u60b2\u9cf4 |access-date=27 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224122708/http://news.tbs.co.jp/newseye/tbs_newseye3911070.html |archive-date=24 February 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In reaction to this problem, [[Hematology|hematologist]] and chairman of the Institute for Healthcare Governance [[:ja:\u4e0a\u660c\u5e83|Masahiro Kami]] claimed that many patients were refused to be tested due to their mild symptoms and criticized the Japanese government for setting testing standards that were too high and for lacking a response to patient anxiety.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u533b\u7642\u6a5f\u95a2\u305f\u3089\u3044\u56de\u3057\u3082 \u7591\u3044\u53d7\u8a3a\u3001\u65ad\u3089\u308c\u2015\u300c\u691c\u67fb\u57fa\u6e96\u3042\u3044\u307e\u3044\u300d\u30fb\u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\uff1a\u6642\u4e8b\u30c9\u30c3\u30c8\u30b3\u30e0 |url=https://www.jiji.com/jc/article?k=2020022300336 |work=\u6642\u4e8b\u901a\u4fe1 |language=ja}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, the Minister of Health Katsunobu stated in the [[National Diet]] that a total of 6,300 samples were tested between 18 and 24 February, averaging 900 samples per day. Some representatives questioned the discrepancy of the actual number of people tested and the claim in the prior week that 3,800 samples could be tested per day.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u66ae\u3089\u3057\u3092\u5b88\u308c \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca \u53d7\u3051\u305f\u304f\u3066\u3082\u306a\u305c \"\u691c\u67fb\u96e3\u6c11\" |url=https://www.fnn.jp/posts/00432813CX/202002261738_CX_CX |work=FNN.jp |language=ja}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, more doctors reported that they were refused by the public health centres to test the patients. The [[Japan Medical Association]] announced that it would start a nationwide investigation and plan to cooperate with the government to improve the situation.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u691c\u67fb\u4f9d\u983c\u3082\u62d2\u5426\u3055\u308c\u308b\u4e8b\u4f8b \u65e5\u672c\u533b\u5e2b\u4f1a\u304c\u8abf\u67fb\u3078 |url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200226/k10012302341000.html |work=NHK|language=ja}}</ref> The Ministry of Health also stated that it would look into the situation with the local governments.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u539a\u52b4\u7701\u3001\uff30\uff23\uff32\u691c\u67fb\u306e\u4e0d\u9069\u5207\u4e8b\u4f8b\u628a\u63e1\u3078 |url=https://news.tbs.co.jp/newseye/tbs_newseye3916025.htm |work=TBS NEWS |language=ja}}</ref>\n\nThe strict constraints on testing for the virus by Japanese health authorities have drawn accusations from critics such as Masahiro Kami towards Abe of wanting to \"downplay the number of infections or patients because of the upcoming Olympics.\" Reports that only a small select number of public health facilities were authorized to test for the virus, after which the results could only be processed by five government-approved companies, has created a bottleneck where clinics have been forced to turn away even patients who had high fevers. This has led some experts to question Japan's official case numbers, with Tobias Harris, of [[Teneo]] Intelligence in Washington, D.C. stating \"You wonder, if they were testing nearly as much as South Korea is testing, what would the actual number be? How many cases are lurking and just aren't being caught?\"<ref name=\"NYT-20FEB29-TestConstraints\">{{Cite news|last=Dooley|first=Ben |last2=Rich|first2=Motoko|last3=Inoue|first3=Makiko | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/japan-elderly-coronavirus.html|title=In Graying Japan, Many Are Vulnerable but Few Are Being Tested|date=29 February 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 February 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-29/japan-s-abe-plans-second-virus-package-of-270-billion-yen|title=Japan's Abe Seeks to Defuse Virus Criticism With Cash, Testing|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|access-date=29 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, the South Korean government criticized the Japanese government for restricting Koreans from entering the country to prevent the disease, saying, \"unreasonable and excessive measures\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus quarantine plans ignite row between South Korea and Japan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/06/coronavirus-quarantine-plans-ignite-row-between-south-korea-and-japan |work=The Guardian |date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Japan and Korea Won't Let A Pandemic Stop Them Fighting |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/12/japan-and-korea-wont-let-a-pandemic-stop-them-fighting/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n<!--\nAccording to reports from the Hong Kong media, Japan is a country that is difficult to trust, and has ignored the German embassy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3077328/coronavirus-german-embassy-criticises-japans-case|date=28 March 2020|title=Coronavirus: German embassy criticises Japan\u2019s case figures as expats question Tokyo\u2019s approach|website=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref> In fact, as restrictions on movement in Tokyo, the representative metropolis of Japan, were alluded to, many shoppers were in a hurry to prepare for this and try to purchase daily necessities ahead of other people who heard that news lately or slowly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3077082/coronavirus-japan-braced-wider-outbreak-no-state-emergency-now|date=26 March 2020|title=Coronavirus: Japan braced for wider outbreak but no state of emergency for now|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> -->\n\n== Regional infection development ==\nThe following are examples of the spread of infections by region in Japan. For reference, the regions are divided into Hokkaido, Tohoku, Kanto, Tokai, Kansai, Hiroshima metropolitan area, and Kyushu region, but only three regions are currently introduced from the densely populated areas of Hokkaido, Kanto, Aichi, Kinki, and Fukuoka. This is a limitation caused by the problem of data citation.\n\n=== Hokkaido ===\nThe first case was identified in [[Hokkaido]] on 28 January 2020,<ref name=\"DoCho_Jokyo\">{{cite web|title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\uff1a\u9053\u5185\u306e\u767a\u751f\u72b6\u6cc1 \uff5c \u4fdd\u5065\u798f\u7949\u90e8\u5065\u5eb7\u5b89\u5168\u5c40\u5730\u57df\u4fdd\u5065\u8ab2|url=http://www.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/hf/kth/kak/hasseijoukyou.htm|website=www.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp|accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref><ref name=\"DoShin200128\">\u201c[https://www.hokkaido-np.co.jp/article/387599 \u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\u60a3\u8005\u3001\u9053\u5185\u3067\u521d\u78ba\u8a8d\u3000\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u5973\u6027\u3001\u9053\u5185\u3067\u5165\u9662]\u201d. \u5317\u6d77\u9053\u65b0\u805e \u96fb\u5b50\u7248 (2020\u5e741\u670828\u65e5). 2020\u5e743\u670825\u65e5\u95b2\u89a7\u3002</ref> and the first case of an infected person in Hokkaido was on 14 February.<ref name=\"DoCho_Jokyo\"/><ref name=\"TomaMin200215\">\u201c[https://www.tomamin.co.jp/article/news/main/12871/ \u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\u3000\u9053\u6c11\u304c\u521d\u611f\u67d3\u3000\uff15\uff10\u4ee3\u7537\u6027\u3001\u5bb9\u4f53\u306f\u91cd\u7be4]\u201d. \u82eb\u5c0f\u7267\u6c11\u5831 \u96fb\u5b50\u7248 (2020\u5e742\u670815\u65e5). 2020\u5e743\u670825\u65e5\u95b2\u89a7\u3002</ref> To limit the spread of infection in Hokkaido, the governor of Hokkaido, Naomichi Suzuki, announced the Declaration of a New Coronavirus Emergency on 28 February of the same year, calling on locals to refrain from going out.<ref name=\"Chiji_Sengen\">\u201c[http://www.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/ss/tkk/koronasengen.htm \u65b0\u305f\u306a\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b8\u3078\uff08\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\uff09\uff5c\u7dcf\u5408\u653f\u7b56\u90e8\u77e5\u4e8b\u5ba4\u5e83\u5831\u5e83\u8074\u8ab2]\u201d. \u5317\u6d77\u9053\u5e81. 2020\u5e743\u670825\u65e5\u95b2\u89a7\u3002</ref>\n\nAs of 9 April 2020, 226 infected people, 10 fatalities, and 149 recoveries were confirmed.<ref name=\"DoCho_nCoV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/ss/tkk/singatakoronahaien.htm |title=\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7\uff08COVID-19\uff09\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u60c5\u5831 |language=ja |publisher=[[Hokkaido|Hokkaido government]] |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"Saishin_Jokyo\">\u201c[http://www.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/hf/kth/kak/hasseijyoukyou_0324genzai.pdf \u5317\u6d77\u9053\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u306b\u95a2\u9023\u3057\u305f\u60a3\u8005\u7b49\u306e\u767a\u751f\u72b6\u6cc1\uff08R2.3.24\u73fe\u5728\uff09]\u201d. \u5317\u6d77\u9053\u5e81. 2020\u5e743\u670830\u65e5\u95b2\u89a7\u3002</ref>\n\n=== Kanto ===\nOn 13 February 2020, three cases of confirmed infection were announced in the [[Kant\u014d region|Kanto]] region, and one case was confirmed in Kanagawa, Tokyo, and Chiba. On 6 March 2020, it was confirmed that 121 infected people were reported in 5 prefectures including Tochigi and Saitama in total. On 21 March, a total of 136 people were identified as infected in Tokyo, and a total of 311 people were confirmed in the Kanto region.\n\nAs of 31 March, a total of 521 people were confirmed infected in Tokyo, and a total of 993 people were confirmed in the Kanto region.\n\n=== Aichi ===\nThe first case was identified in [[Aichi Prefecture|Aichi]] on 26 January 2020,<ref name=\"Aichi1\"/> and the first case of an infected person in Aichi was on 14 February.<ref name=\"Aichi1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pref.aichi.jp/site/covid19-aichi/kansensya-kensa.html|title=\u611b\u77e5\u770c\u5185\u306e\u611f\u67d3\u8005\u30fb\u907a\u4f1d\u5b50\u691c\u67fb\u4ef6\u6570 - \u611b\u77e5\u770c|website=www.pref.aichi.jp|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> As the spread of the new coronavirus continues, Governor Omura of Aichi Prefecture has recognized that there are two groups of infected people called \"clusters\" in the prefecture, mainly in Nagoya.<ref name=\"Nagoya2\"/> He emphasised the idea of working with Nagoya City Government to prevent the spread of infection.<ref name=\"Nagoya2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200305/k10012315621000.html|date=5 March 2020||title=\u300c\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc \u540d\u53e4\u5c4b\u5e02\u4e2d\u5fc3\u306b\uff12\u3064\u767a\u751f\u300d\u611b\u77e5\u770c\u77e5\u4e8b|website=[[NHK]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nAs of 26 March 2020, 18 fatalities were reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200326/k10012350501000.html|date=26 March 2020|title=\u611b\u77e5 \u6b7b\u4ea1\u306f18\u4eba \u611f\u67d3\u78ba\u8a8d\u306f154\u4eba\u306b \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=ja}}</ref> As of 30 March 2020, 170 infected people were confirmed.<ref>\u201c[https://www.pref.aichi.jp/uploaded/attachment/329268.pdf \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u75c7 \u770c\u5185\u767a\u751f\u4e8b\u4f8b]\u201d. \u611b\u77e5\u9053\u5e81. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Socio-economic impact==\n[[File:NoMasksLeft2020.jpg|thumb|Shelves in a pharmacy in Japan sold out of masks on 3 February 2020|alt=]]\nPrime Minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] said that \"the new coronavirus is having a major impact on tourism, the economy and our society as a whole\".<ref name=\"20200201japantimesA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/01/national/shinzo-abe-combat-coronavirus-outbreak-japan/|title=Japan reports 20th case of coronavirus as Abe vows new steps to combat outbreak|date=1 February 2020|work=Japan Times|access-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201160519/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/01/national/shinzo-abe-combat-coronavirus-outbreak-japan/|archive-date=1 February 2020|issn=0447-5763}}</ref><ref name=\"20200201japantimesB\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/01/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/south-korea-says-chinese-tour-guide-arriving-japan-found-infected-coronavirus/|title=South Korea says Chinese tour guide arriving from Japan found to be infected with coronavirus|date=1 February 2020|work=Japan Times|access-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201134136/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/01/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/south-korea-says-chinese-tour-guide-arriving-japan-found-infected-coronavirus/|archive-date=1 February 2020|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> Face masks have sold out across the nation and stocks of face masks are depleted within a day of new arrivals.<ref name=\"20200131japantimes\">{{Cite news|last=Takahashi|first=Ryusei|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/31/national/coronavirus-japan-surgical-masks/|title=Amid virus outbreak, Japan stores scramble to meet demand for face masks|date=31 January 2020|work=Japan Times|access-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201141824/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/31/national/coronavirus-japan-surgical-masks/|archive-date=1 February 2020|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> There has been pressure placed on the healthcare system as demands for [[physical examination|medical checkups]] increase.<ref name=\"20200201reutersB\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-japan-idUSKBN1ZV3GZ|title=Japan seeks to contain economic impact of virus, new measures come into effect|date=1 February 2020|access-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201133549/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-japan-idUSKBN1ZV3GZ|archive-date=1 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> Chinese people have reported increasing discrimination.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pfanner|first=Eric|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/30/world/chinese-tourists-finding-no-longer-welcome-fear-coronavirus-takes-hold/|title=Chinese tourists finding they are no longer welcome as fear over coronavirus takes hold|date=30 January 2020|work=Japan Times|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131064332/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/30/world/chinese-tourists-finding-no-longer-welcome-fear-coronavirus-takes-hold/|archive-date=31 January 2020|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|health minister]] has pointed out that the situation had not reached a point where mass gatherings must be called off.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/national/3-Japanese-returnees-from-Wuhan-test-positive-for-new-coronavirus|title=3 Japanese returnees from Wuhan test positive for new coronavirus|website=Japan Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130140241/https://japantoday.com/category/national/3-Japanese-returnees-from-Wuhan-test-positive-for-new-coronavirus|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAviation, retail and tourism sectors have reported decreased sales and some manufacturers have complained about disruption to Chinese factories, logistics and supply chains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/will-japans-economy-buckle-under-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Will Japan's Economy Buckle Under the Coronavirus Outbreak?|last=Siripala|first=Thisanka|date=13 February 2020|website=thediplomat.com|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister Abe has considered using emergency funds to mitigate the outbreak's impact on tourism, of which Chinese nationals account for 40%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/japan-considers-extra-spending-over-coronavirus-e2-80-99s-impact-on-tourism/ar-BBZvrUa|title=Japan Considers Extra Spending Over Coronavirus's Impact on Tourism|author=Nohara, Yoshiaki|date=31 January 2020|publisher=MSN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131083426/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/japan-considers-extra-spending-over-coronavirus-e2-80-99s-impact-on-tourism/ar-BBZvrUa|archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> S&P Global noted that the worst hit shares were from companies spanning travel, cosmetics and retail sectors which are most exposed to Chinese tourism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spglobal.com/en/research-insights/articles/chinese-coronavirus-fear-spreads-over-luxury-retail-sectors|title=Chinese coronavirus fear spreads over luxury, retail sectors|website=spglobal.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201140526/https://www.spglobal.com/en/research-insights/articles/chinese-coronavirus-fear-spreads-over-luxury-retail-sectors|archive-date=1 February 2020|access-date=1 February 2020}}</ref> [[Nintendo]] warned that delays on shipments for hardware and accessories for its [[Nintendo Switch]] [[video game console]] would be \"unavoidable\" due to the impact on its Chinese supply chain and manufacturing, and on 7 April announced that shipments to Japan would be delayed due to increased demand for the device.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2020-02-06/coronavirus-delays-nintendo-switch-production-shipments-for-japan/.156176|title=Coronavirus Delays Nintendo Switch Production, Shipments for Japan|website=Anime News Network}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Companies/Nintendo-halts-Switch-shipments-in-Japan-as-orders-surge|title=Nintendo halts Switch shipments in Japan as orders surge|website=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThe [[governor of Hokkaido]], [[Naomichi Suzuki]], declared a state of emergency due to the high number of new infections and asked citizens to stay at home that following weekend.<ref>[https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/69d1b85128b9-urgent-hokkaido-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus.html Hokkaido declares state of emergency over coronavirus]. ''Kyodo News'', 28 February 2020.</ref>\n\n===Sporting events===\n[[File:\"wash your hands\" announce in Tokaido Shinkansen during Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|An announcement urging travellers to wash their hands in Tokaido Shinkansen]]\n{{see also| Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the 2020 Summer Olympics}}\n\nThe outbreak has affected professional sports in Japan. [[Nippon Professional Baseball]]'s preseason games and the [[2020 in sumo#Haru basho|Haru Basho sumo tournament]] in [[Osaka]] were announced to be held [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]], while the [[J.League]] football and [[Top League]] rugby suspended or postponed play entirely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/5248dbcddb58-update2-sumo-spring-meet-unlikely-to-be-held-in-regular-fashion-jsa.html|title=Sumo: Spring meet unlikely to be held in \"regular\" fashion: JSA|date=28 February 2020|work=Kyodo News|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> On the weekend of 29 February, the [[Japan Racing Association]] closed its [[horse racing]] meets to spectators and [[off-track betting]] until further notice, but continued to offer wagering by phone and online.<ref>[https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/238823/coronavirus-forces-bettors-online-in-japan Coronavirus Forces Bettors Online in Japan ]</ref>\n\nThe expansion of COVID-19 into a global pandemic led to concerns over the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] and [[2020 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]] in Tokyo. In March 2020, it was announced that the Games would be postponed by a year, for the first time in the history of the modern Olympics.<ref name=\"IOC_2021_Dates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-ipc-tokyo-2020-organising-committee-and-tokyo-metropolitan-government-announce-new-dates-for-the-olympic-and-paralympic-games-tokyo-2020|title=IOC, IPC, Tokyo 2020 Organising Committee and Tokyo Metropolitan Government Announce New Dates for the Olympic and Paralympic Games Tokyo 2020|date=2020-03-30|website=olympic.org|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1092594/postponed-tokyo-olympics-july-23-opening|title=Rescheduled Tokyo 2020 Olympics to open on July 23 in 2021|last=Pavitt|first=Michael|date=20 March 2020|website=insidethegames.biz|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television}}\nOn 26 February, Prime Minister Shinzo Abe has suggested that major sporting, cultural and other events should be cancelled, delayed or scaled down for about two weeks amid the new coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200226_28/|date=26 February 2020|work=NHK World Japan|accessdate=16 March 2020|language=en|title=Abe: Next 2 weeks 'crucial' in virus battle NHK WORLD-JAPAN News}}</ref> As a result, [[J-pop]] groups [[Perfume (Japanese band)|Perfume]] and [[Exile (Japanese band)|Exile]] cancelled their concerts scheduled that night at [[Tokyo Dome]] and [[Kyocera Dome Osaka]] respectively, both of which have a capacity of 55,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/4d5ff5744493-urgent-abe-asks-big-event-organizers-to-mull-cancelations-for-next-2-weeks.html|date=27 February 2020|work= KYODO NEWS|accessdate=5 April 2020|language=en|title=Organizers asked for event cancellations for 2 weeks amid coronavirus spread}}</ref> On 27 February, [[AnimeJapan]] 2020, originally scheduled to be held in [[Tokyo Big Sight]] in late March, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itmedia.co.jp/news/articles/2002/27/news110.html|date=27 February 2020|work=IT Media|accessdate=6 March 2020|language=ja|script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u300cAnimeJapan 2020\u300d\u3082\u4e2d\u6b62\u3000\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u306e\u62e1\u5927\u3067}}</ref>\n\nA number of major [[Amusement park|amusement parks]] announced temporary closures; on 28 February 2020, [[Tokyo Disneyland]], [[Tokyo DisneySea]] and [[Tokyo Disney Resort]] were temporarily closed from 29 February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disneyland-idUSKBN20Y0KL|title=Tokyo Disneyland to stay closed through early April due to virus|date=2020-03-11|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-11/tokyo-disneyland-extends-shutdown-may-see-longest-ever-closure|title=Tokyo Disneyland Extends Shutdown, May See Longest-Ever Closure|date=2020-03-11|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live|website=}}</ref> [[Universal Studios Japan]] also announced a closure the same day.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Davis|first=River|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-puts-hopes-pinned-to-tokyo-olympics-tourists-in-jeopardy-11584612940|title=Coronavirus Puts Hopes Pinned to Tokyo Olympics Tourists in Jeopardy|date=2020-03-19|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> By mid-March, some attractions began to re-open to extents, with [[Huis Ten Bosch (theme park)|Huis Ten Bosch]] and [[Legoland Japan Resort]] reopening with limited services (outdoor attractions only, visitors subject to temperature checks before entering) on 23 March.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bevil|first1=Dewayne|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/coronavirus/os-ne-coronavirus-legoland-florida-reopening-20200320-ux4ueco3qzhilbucsigkoovkua-story.html|title=Legoland Japan set to reopen Monday after 3-week coronavirus closure|date=20 March 2020|work=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Japan-quietly-reopens-as-much-of-world-locks-down|title=Japan quietly reopens as much of world locks down|website=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> However, the Disney parks and Universal Studios Japan have since delayed their re-openings until mid-to-late April, with the Disney parks targeting at least 20 April.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/national/tokyo-disneyland-won%27t-reopen-before-april-20-operator-says|title=Tokyo Disneyland won't reopen before April 20, operator says|website=Japan Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20200327_38/|title=Major theme parks in Japan extend closures|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=NHK World|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAffected by the shortage of outsourced staff due to the COVID-19 outbreak, many Japanese animated films and TV shows announced changes or postponed broadcasts due to production problems, including ''[[A Certain Scientific Railgun T]]'' (deferred for broadcast, changed to rebroadcast), ''[[Asteroid in Love]]'', ''[[:ja:A3!|A3!]]'' (Delay extension), ''[[Kukuriraige -Sanxingdui Fantasy-]]'' (Delay extension), etc.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itmedia.co.jp/news/articles/2002/17/news124.html|date=17 February 2020|work=IT Media|accessdate=6 March 2020|language=ja|script-title=ja:\u6771\u4eacMX\u3001\u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\u3067\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300c\u3068\u3042\u308b\u79d1\u5b66\u306e\u8d85\u96fb\u78c1\u7832T\u300d\u653e\u9001\u5ef6\u671f\u3000\u300c\u5236\u4f5c\u4e0a\u306e\u90fd\u5408\u304c\u3064\u304b\u305a\u300d}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animatetimes.com/news/details.php?id=1581650595|work=Animate Times|accessdate=6 March 2020|language=ja|script-title=ja:TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300eA3!\u300f\u300cSEASON SPRING & SUMMER\u300d\u7b2c4\u8a71\u4ee5\u964d\u306e\u653e\u9001\u304c\u5ef6\u671f\u306b}}</ref> On 31 March, [[TV Asahi]] announced that Rio Komiya, who plays J\u016bru Atsuta in the [[Tokusatsu|toku]] series ''[[Mashin Sentai Kiramager]]'', had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/18048897/|title=\u300c\u9b54\u9032\u6226\u968a\u30ad\u30e9\u30e1\u30a4\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u300d\u4e3b\u4eba\u516c\u5f79\u306e\u5c0f\u5bae\u7483\u592e\u304c\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u611f\u67d3|date=31 March 2020|publisher=Livedoor|language=ja|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tokusatsunetwork.com/2020/03/kiramei-red-actor-rio-komiya-tests-positive-for-covid-19/|title=ACTOR NEWSKiramaRed Actor Rio Komiya Tests Positive for COVID-19|date=31 March 2020|publisher=Tokusatsu Network|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> While production had been suspended, it was stated that there were still enough completed episodes remaining to last through mid-May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/news/202003310000456.html|title=\u6771\u6620\u6771\u4eac\u64ae\u5f71\u6240\u306f\u6d88\u6bd2\u4f5c\u696d\u3000\u30ec\u30c3\u30c9\u5f79\u304c\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u967d\u6027|date=31 March 2020|publisher=Nikkan Sports|language=ja|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/japan-toei-closes-tokyo-studio-coronavirus-infection-1203549908/|title=Japan's Toei Closes Tokyo Studio After Coronavirus Infection|date=31 March 2020|publisher=Variety|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, it was announced that famed Japanese comedian [[Ken Shimura]] had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/japan-ken-shimura-coronavirus-god-of-cinema-filming-halted-1203544266/|title=Japan's Ken Shimura Infected by Coronavirus, 'God of Cinema' Filming Halted|last=Schilling|first=Mark|date=2020-03-25|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"Shimura\" /> Shimura died on 29 March at the age of 70.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Obituaries/Japan-comedian-Ken-Shimura-dies-after-coronavirus-infection2|date=29 March 2020|title=Japan comedian Ken Shimura dies after coronavirus infection|publisher=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-japan-comedian/japanese-comedian-ken-shimura-dies-from-coronavirus-idUSKBN21H020|date=29 March 2020|title=Japanese comedian Ken Shimura dies from coronavirus|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Aid to China ===\nOn 26 January, Japanese people donated a batch of epidemic prevention masks and delivered them to Wuhan after [[Sichuan Airlines]] arrived in Chengdu.<ref name=\"\u62a5\u90530126D\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guancha.cn/internation/2020_01_26_533209.shtml|title=\u65e5\u672c\u6c11\u95f4\u6350100\u4e07\u53e3\u7f69\u9a70\u63f4\u6b66\u6c49|author1=\u9f99\u73a5|website=\u89c2\u5bdf\u8005\u7f51|location=Shanghai|language=zh-cn|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> According to \"liberal digital times\" of Taiwan, it believes that instead of donating from Japan, China bought from Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/3050662|title=\u300a\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u300b\u4e2d\u570b\u81ea\u55e8\uff1f\u65e5\u5a92\uff1a\u65e5\u672c\u6350\u767e\u842c\u53e3\u7f69 \u4e8b\u4e3b\u51fa\u9762\u6253\u81c9 - \u570b\u969b - \u81ea\u7531\u6642\u5831\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|date=27 January 2020|work=\u81ea\u7531\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|language=zh-TW|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128135649/https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/breakingnews/3050662|archive-date=28 January 2020|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> but according to Japanese media reports and the {{ill|Consulate General of Japan in Chongqing|lt=Japanese Consulate General in Chongqing|ja|\u5728\u91cd\u6176\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u7dcf\u9818\u4e8b\u9928}} stated that it was a donation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20200128-00010004-bfj-soci|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u306b100\u4e07\u679a\u4ee5\u4e0a\u306e\u30de\u30b9\u30af\u5bc4\u4ed8\u3002\u65e5\u672c\u4f01\u696d\u3084\u5e02\u3001\u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9\u611f\u67d3\u62e1\u5927\u3067|date=28 January 2020|publisher=Yahoo! Japan|language=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"choce\">{{cite web|url=https://m.weibo.cn/detail/4465757263810401|title=\u65e5\u672c\u6c34\u6237\u5e02\u5411\u91cd\u5e86\u5e02\u6350\u8d6050000\u4efd\u533b\u7528\u53e3\u7f69|author=Consulate General of Japan in Chongqing|date=28 January 2020|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130103406/https://m.weibo.cn/detail/4465757263810401|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February, four organizations, the Japan Pharmaceutical NPO Corporation, the Japan Hubei Federation, [[Huobi|Huobi Global]], and Incuba Alpha, donated materials to Hubei and wrote, \"Is it clothesless? With the same clothes.\" (From \"Book of Songs \u00b7 Qin Feng \u00b7 No Clothes\") and \"An Exotic Mountain and River, Same Wind and Moon\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guancha.cn/internation/2020_02_04_534497.shtml|title=\"\u5c71\u5ddd\u7570\u57df\uff0c\u98a8\u6708\u540c\u5929\"\uff1a\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u611f\u8b1d\u65e5\u672c\u5354\u52a9\u6297\u75ab\u7684\u6696\u5fc3\u8209\u52d5|date=4 February 2020|access-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205085252/https://www.guancha.cn/internation/2020_02_04_534497.shtml|archive-date=5 February 2020|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]]'s Secretary General [[Toshihiro Nikai]] said at a press conference after the cadre meeting that the outbreak of coronavirus in mainland China has expanded, the Liberal Democratic Party will deduct 5,000 yen from the March funding of members of the party to provide mainland China with support funds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://zh.cn.nikkei.com/politicsaeconomy/politicsasociety/39325-2020-02-11-09-11-18.html|title=\u65e5\u672c\u57f7\u653f\u9ee8\u570b\u6703\u8b70\u54e1\u6bcf\u4eba\u5c07\u5411\u4e2d\u570b\u6350\u6b3e5000\u65e5\u5143|access-date=14 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211170229/http://zh.cn.nikkei.com/politicsaeconomy/politicsasociety/39325-2020-02-11-09-11-18.html|archive-date=15 February 2020|publisher=The Nikkei|language=zh}}</ref>\n\n== Festivals and contests ==\nThe following major festivals were cancelled:\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Sapporo Yosakoi Soran Festival\n*[[Hirosaki]] [[cherry blossom]] festival in [[Aomori Prefecture]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Kaila Imada|title=100-year-old Hirosaki Cherry Blossom Festival in Aomori is cancelled this year|url=https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/news/100-year-old-hirosaki-cherry-blossom-festival-in-aomori-is-cancelled-this-year-040620|work=Time Out Tokyo|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Aomori Nebuta Matsuri]] in several cities in Aomori Prefecture<ref>{{cite news|title=\u9ed2\u77f3\u306d\u3077\u305f\u796d\u308a\u4e2d\u6b62\u6c7a\u5b9a\u3000\uff16\uff15\u5e74\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u3067\u521d|trans-title=Kuroishi Neputa Matsuri cancelled for the first time in its 65-year-long history|url=http://www.mutusinpou.co.jp/news/2020/04/59395.html|language=ja|newspaper=Mutsu Shimp\u014d|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u9752\u68ee\u306d\u3076\u305f\u796d\u4e2d\u6b62 \u6b63\u5f0f\u6c7a\u5b9a \u65b0\u578b\u30b3\u30ed\u30ca\u30a6\u30a4\u30eb\u30b9|trans-title=Officials cancel Aomori Nebuta Festival due to coronavirus|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20200408/k10012375521000.html|language=ja|work=NHK|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Akita Kanto Festival\n*Aoba festival of [[Sendai]]\n*Sendai Tanabata Festival\n*Fukushima Waraji Festival\n*[[Hiratsuka]] [[Tanabata]] Festival\n*[[Odawara]] Hojo Festival\n*[[Shingen Takeda]] traditional festival in [[Kofu]]\n*Shizuoka festival\n*[[Hamamatsu Kite Festival]]\n*[[Takayama Festival|Spring Takayama Festival]] in [[Gifu Prefecture]]\n{{col-2}}\n*Tado festival of [[Kuwana]], [[Mie Prefecture]]\n*Hyakumangoku Festival of [[Kanazawa]]\n*[[Aoi Festival]] of [[Kyoto]]\n*[[Gion Matsuri|Gion Festival]] of Kyoto \n*Tenjin Matsuri of [[Osaka]]\n*Kobe festival\n*[[Awa Odori]] of [[Tokushima City]]\n*Hiroshima Flower Festival\n*Shimonoseki Strait Festival in [[Yamaguchi Prefecture]]\n*[[Hakata Dontaku]] in [[Fukuoka]]\n*Hakata Gion Yanakasa of Fukuoka\n{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n*Corona Sunsets Festival, in [[Okinawa]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://corona-sunsets.jp/experience/corona-sunsets-festival-2020/ | title=CORONA SUNSETS FESTIVAL 2020 \u306e\u958b\u50ac\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 &#124; Corona SUNSETS FESTIVAL}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n*[[Sanja festival]], originally scheduled from 15-17 May, has been changed to October in Tokyo{{page needed|date=April 2020}} \n\n*2020 Japan Tree-planting Festival (\u5168\u56fd\u690d\u6a39\u796d) in [[Shimane Prefecture]], originally scheduled for 31 May, it postponement date is unknown{{page needed|date=April 2020}} \n\n*2020 Tohoku Kizuna Traditional Festival (\u6771\u5317\u7d46\u796d\u308a) in [[Yamagata City]], originally schedule date on May 30 to 31, it has been changed to until next July{{page needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nThe following major fireworks events were also cancelled:\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Nagaoka, Niigata|Nagaoka]] Firework Festival in [[Niigata Prefecture]]\n*[[Sumida River]] Firework Festival in Tokyo\n*[[Kumano River]] Firework Festival in Mie Prefecture\n{{col-2}}\n*[[PL Kyodan|Perfect Liberty]] Firework Festival in [[Osaka Prefecture]] \n*[[Miyajima]] Underwater Firework Festival in [[Hiroshima Prefecture]]{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n*Naniwa [[Yodo River]] Firework Festival in Osaka, originally schedule date on August 8, has been changed to August 22{{page needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nThe following major contests were cancelled or postponed indefinitely:\n*All Japan [[Kokeshi]] contest and exhibition in [[Shiroishi, Miyagi|Shiroishi]], [[Miyagi Prefecture]]\n*All Japan [[Chindon'ya|chindonya]] contest in [[Toyama City]]\n*Fukiage beach [[sand sculpture]] contest and exhibition in [[Minamisatsuma]], [[Kagoshima Prefecture]]{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n*Arida Pottery Market in [[Saga Prefecture]], originally scheduled for 29 April to 5 May, has been postponed indefinitely{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== International travel restrictions ==\n=== Restrictions on entry to Japan ===\nOn 3 April, foreign travellers who had been in any of the following countries and regions within the past 14 days were barred from entering Japan:<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) advisory information {{!}} Travel Japan {{!}} JNTO |url=https://www.japan.travel/en/coronavirus/ |website=Japan National Tourism Organization (JNTO) |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width: 100pt;\" | Asia\n| [[Brunei]], [[China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Indonesia]], [[Macau]], [[Malaysia]], [[Philippines]], [[South Korea]], [[Singapore]], [[Taiwan]], [[Thailand]], [[Vietnam]]\n|-\n! Oceania\n| [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]]\n|-\n! Middle East\n| [[Bahrain]], [[Iran]], [[Israel]], [[Turkey]]\n|-\n! Europe\n| [[Albania]], [[Andorra]], [[Armenia]], [[Austria]], [[Belgium]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Croatia]], [[Cyprus]], [[Czechia]], [[Denmark]], [[Estonia]], [[Finland]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Iceland]], [[Ireland]], [[Italy]], [[Kosovo]], [[Latvia]], [[Liechtenstein]], [[Lithuania]], [[Luxembourg]], [[Malta]], [[Moldova]], [[Monaco]], [[Montenegro]], [[Netherlands]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Norway]], [[Poland]], [[Portugal]], [[Romania]], [[San Marino]], [[Serbia]], [[Slovakia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Spain]], [[Sweden]], [[Switzerland]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Vatican City]]\n|-\n! Africa\n| [[C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Egypt]], [[Mauritius]], [[Morocco]]\n|-\n! North America\n| [[Canada]], [[United States]]\n|-\n! Latin America & Caribbean\n| [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]], [[Chile]], [[Dominica]], [[Ecuador]], [[Panama]]\n|}\n\n=== Restrictions on entry from Japan ===\nThe following countries and territories have restricted entry from Japan:{{Div col}}\n*{{flag|Algeria}}<ref name=\":3\" />\n*{{flag|Angola}}<ref name=\":3\" />\n*{{flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}<ref name=\":3\" />\n*{{Flag|Argentina}}: Flight suspension an