{"title_page": "Kim Young-joo (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean politician}}\n{{About|South Korean politician and former minister|South Korean football referee|Kim Young-joo}}{{Infobox officeholder\n| native_name         = {{nobold|\uae40\uc601\uc8fc}}\n| office1             = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| birth_place         = [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]\n| termend2            = 29 May 2008\n| termstart2          = 30 May 2004\n| termstart1          = 30 May 2012\n| constituency2       = Proportional representation\n| constituency1       = [[Seoul]] [[Yeongdeungpo]] A\n| successor           = Lee Jae-gap\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1955|07|27|df=y}}\n| termend             = 21 September 2018\n| termstart           = 14 August 2017\n| primeminister       = [[Lee Nak-yeon]]\n| president           = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n| office              = [[Ministry of Employment and Labor|Minister of Employment and Labor]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Korea National Open University]]<br>[[Sogang University]]\n}}\n{{Korean name}}\n\n'''Kim Young-joo''' ({{korean|hangul=\uae40\uc601\uc8fc|hanja=\u91d1\u69ae\u73e0|rr=|mr=}}; born 27 July 1955) is a [[South Korea]]n basketball-player-turned politician previously served as President [[Moon Jae-in]]'s first [[Ministry of Employment and Labor|Minister of Employment and Labor]]. She is the first woman to lead the Ministry since its creation in 1981 and its preceding agency in 1948.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://pulsenews.co.kr/view.php?year=2017&no=495786|title=Korea\u2019s first cabinet under new president almost complete with Kim Young-joo named as labor minister - Pulse by Maeil Business News Korea|website=pulsenews.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nShe was a basketball player for Seoul Trust Bank (now absorbed into [[Hana Bank]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> She then worked at the Bank where she faced gender discrimination which led her to join its trade union. She later joined its leadership board and eventually became the deputy chair of Korea Financial Industry Union and the first woman to assume this post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170723000128|title=Former basketball player, labor minister nominee champions gender equality|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2017-07-23|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999 she first entered into politics when she was recruited by [[Kim Dae-jung]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20170723/85483656/2|title=\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9 \"\uae40\uc601\uc8fc \uace0\uc6a9\ubd80\uc7a5\uad00 \ud6c4\ubcf4\uc790 \ub0b4\uc815, \uc9c4\uc2ec\uc73c\ub85c \ud658\uc601\"|date=2017-07-23|website=www.donga.com|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> She has consistently took senior roles in her party and its preceding parties such as its secretary-general and one of elected members of its Supreme Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moel.go.kr/cyber/intro/hist/view.do?seq=58|title=\uace0\uc6a9\ub178\ub3d9\ubd80 \uc5f4\ub9b0\uc7a5\uad00\uc2e4|website=www.moel.go.kr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nShe was nominated and appointed as President [[Moon Jae-in]]'s first Minister of Employment and Labor. She was replaced after facing opposition parties and media's strong critics of \"52-hour workweek and increased minimum wage\" policy, which she was responsible of as Minister and was one of main socio-economic campaign promises of Moon, throughout her time as Minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2018/08/31/Top-South-Korea-officials-replaced-in-Moon-Jae-in-government/3651535698933/|title=Top South Korea officials replaced in Moon Jae-in government|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nKim earned her undergraduate degree in Korean language and literature from [[Korea National Open University]] and master's degree in economics from [[Sogang University]] in her 40s.\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Election\n!Year\n!District\n!Party Affiliation\n!Votes\n!Percentage of votes\n!Results\n|-\n|16th National Assembly General Election\n|2000\n|Proportional representation\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2000)|Democratic Party (2000)]]\n|6,780,625 \n|35.9%\n|Lost\n|-\n|17th National Assembly General Election\n|2004\n|Proportional representation\n|[[Uri Party]]\n|8,145,824 \n|38.26%\n|Won\n|-\n|18th National Assembly General Election\n|2008\n|[[Seoul]] [[Yeongdeungpo District|Yeongdeungpo]] A\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2008)|Democratic Party (2008)]]\n|34,163 \n|42.53%\n|Lost\n|-\n|19th National Assembly General Election\n|2012\n|[[Seoul]] [[Yeongdeungpo District|Yeongdeungpo]] A\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic United Party]]\n|52,232 \n|52.87%\n|Won\n|-\n|20th National Assembly General Election\n|2014\n|[[Seoul]] [[Yeongdeungpo District|Yeongdeungpo]] A\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|49,935 \n|45.28%\n|Won\n|-\n|21st National Assembly General Election\n|2020\n|[[Seoul]] [[Yeongdeungpo District|Yeongdeungpo]] A\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|72,445 \n|56.2%\n|Won\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean politicians]]\n[[Category:Korea University alumni]]\n[[Category:Korea National Open University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sogang University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Seoul]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean politician}}\n{{About|South Korean politician and former minister|South Korean football referee|Kim Young-joo}}{{Infobox officeholder\n| native_name         = {{nobold|\uae40\uc601\uc8fc}}\n| office1             = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| birth_place         = [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]\n| termend2            = 29 